"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715099","Home Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>The Home Office is continuing to assess and analyse elements of the exit check data collected in relation to specific cohorts to understand the extent to which estimates provided are statistically robust. This level of detail is not yet available.</p><p> </p><p>Over time the data obtained through exit checks will contribute to the statistical picture.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-04-18T15:54:12.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715099/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715099/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-29","Visas: Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what evidence the data from the exit checks introduced in 2015 gives on the proportion of international students who break the terms of their visa.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","69838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715100","Home Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>The performance the three COMPASS service providers is monitored via the Key Performance Indicator (KPI) regime, details of which are set out in their contracts and cover the provision of the whole service. The Home Office has a rigorous contract compliance regime in place to ensure that the required performance standards expected are met.</p><p>This includes monthly contract management and quarterly strategic review meetings, as well as regular daily discussions with COMPASS providers’ operational delivery managers about day to day issues. Performance against each key performance indicator (KPI) is measured and may, dependent upon the level of non-conformance, lead to the application of a KPI score. The overall/total score across all KPIs is then used to determine the value of Service Credit (rebate) which should be deducted from the monthly invoice. Over the lifetime of the contracts, the performance of all of the providers against KPI regime has improved.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-04-18T15:58:08.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715100/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715100/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-29","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the number of occasions and reasons why Compass has breached its (a) key performance indicators and (b) performance standards in each year since the start of that company's contract.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","69759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715101","Home Office","false","2017-04-20","<p>The current policy, which requires the countersignatory to be a person of professional standing, is not prescriptive in relation to acceptable professions. The current list of recognised professions on Gov.UK is intended to be purely illustrative to assist the public, and it is therefore unnecessary to expand this list.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-04-20T08:31:40.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715101/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715101/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715101/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-29","Passports: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she last reviewed the list of accepted occupations for passport application and photo countersignatories; and whether she plans to increase the number of accepted occupations on that list.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","69739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715102","Home Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>The published service standard for the Employer Checking Service is 5 working days but the average processing time between 01/11/2011 and 28/02/2017 was 4.5 working days.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-04-18T15:53:18.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715102/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715102/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-29","Immigrants: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average time taken to process checks by the Employer Checking Service is.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","69725"
