"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715104","Home Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>No psychiatrists currently on a Tier 2 visa will attract the immigration skills charge.</p><p>The immigration skills charge will not apply where an individual has already been assigned a Tier 2 Certificate of Sponsorship at the time the regulations come into force.</p><p>There is also an exemption to the immigration skills charge for PhD level occupations.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-04-18T15:56:26.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715104/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715104/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715104/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-29","Psychiatry: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of psychiatrists currently on a Tier 2 visa who will attract the immigration skills charge.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","69686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715105","Home Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>ONS release annual figures on breakdown of Civil Servants across all government departments.</p><p> </p><p>For 2016, there were 26,540 FTE under the Home Office which is the home department of UK Visas and Immigration.</p><p> </p><p>Staff resources are moved between teams as the demands of the work require and have been supported from other departments with cross-working throughout 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-04-18T16:00:07.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715105/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715105/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715105/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-29","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she has taken to ensure that UK Visas and Immigration can manage the increased level of EU casework since January 2015.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","69674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715106","Home Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>ONS release annual figures on breakdown of Civil Servants across all government departments.</p><p> </p><p>For 2016, there were 26,540 FTE under the Home Office which is the home department of UK Visas and Immigration.</p><p> </p><p>Staff resources are moved between teams as the demands of the work require and have been supported from other departments with cross-working throughout 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-04-18T17:00:00.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715106/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715106/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715106/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-29","UK Visas and Immigration: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many and what proportion of UK Visas and Immigration staff were employed to process EU casework in each month since January 2016.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","69675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715107","Home Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>The Government supports the use of encryption. Encryption plays an important role in promoting cyber security, the prevention of cyber-crime, and protecting information online. Strong encryption - as practiced by many of the biggest names online - is central to the working of the internet.</p><p>But we must be clear that there is a balance to be struck. As those charged with keeping us all safe, the police and the security and intelligence agencies must have the tools they need to do their jobs. One of those tools is the ability to read, where it is both necessary and proportionate, the encrypted messages of those who plan and commit terrorist attacks and serious crimes.</p><p>We have well-established, constructive working relationships with a wide-range of groups with an interest in this area – including the major Communications Service Providers and business representatives – and we will continue to engage with them, along with other partners, to together find a solution that both permits law enforcement and the security and intelligence agencies to get the information they need, whilst also protecting privacy.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","69677","2017-04-18T16:50:52.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715107/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715107/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715107/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-29","Cryptography","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the effect on consumer security of prohibiting end-to-end encryption.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","69676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715108","Home Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>The Government supports the use of encryption. Encryption plays an important role in promoting cyber security, the prevention of cyber-crime, and protecting information online. Strong encryption - as practiced by many of the biggest names online - is central to the working of the internet.</p><p>But we must be clear that there is a balance to be struck. As those charged with keeping us all safe, the police and the security and intelligence agencies must have the tools they need to do their jobs. One of those tools is the ability to read, where it is both necessary and proportionate, the encrypted messages of those who plan and commit terrorist attacks and serious crimes.</p><p>We have well-established, constructive working relationships with a wide-range of groups with an interest in this area – including the major Communications Service Providers and business representatives – and we will continue to engage with them, along with other partners, to together find a solution that both permits law enforcement and the security and intelligence agencies to get the information they need, whilst also protecting privacy.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","69676","2017-04-18T16:50:52.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715108/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715108/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715108/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-29","Cryptography: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment she has made of the contribution to national security of prohibiting end-to-end encryption in digital messaging.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","69677"
