ng></p></td><td><p>24,420</p></td><td><p>7,970</p></td><td><p>14,990</p></td><td><p>1,460</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>May 2015</strong></p></td><td><p>22,750</p></td><td><p>7,400</p></td><td><p>13,995</p></td><td><p>1,350</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>May 2016</strong></p></td><td><p>20,790</p></td><td><p>6,890</p></td><td><p>12,680</p></td><td><p>1,220</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><ol><li>Source: Single Housing Benefit Extract (SHBE) administrative data.</li><li>Figures have been rounded to the nearest 5 and may not sum due to rounding.</li></ol>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","69772 ; 69773 ; 69774 ; 69777","2017-04-19T11:39:27.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715174/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715174/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-29","Housing Benefit: Liverpool City Region","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many households in Liverpool City Region in receipt of housing benefit subject to the spare room subsidy were living in (a) two or (b) three bedroom properties in each year since April 2013.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","69778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715175","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government takes into account the implications for Housing Benefit expenditure when considering policies for social and affordable housing.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-04-24T14:45:20.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715175/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715175/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-29","Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of building council housing as a means of reducing housing benefit expenditure.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","69724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715176","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-18","<p>The benefit cap was lowered on the 7th November from £26,000 to £20,000, except in London where it was lowered to £23,000 (a lower cap applies to single adult households).</p><p> </p><p>To help ensure Local Authorities are able to protect the most vulnerable Housing Benefit claimants and to support households adjusting to our welfare reforms, the Government will provide over £800m funding for Discretionary Housing Payments over the next 5 years from 2016/17. Information about this and other measures to ease the transition for families affected by this policy change is included in the latest impact assessment at the link below.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/welfare-reform-and-work-act-impact-assessment-for-the-benefit-cap" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/welfare-reform-and-work-act-impact-assessment-for-the-benefit-cap</a></p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-04-18T14:11:26.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715176/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715176/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715176/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-29","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's impact assessment of 25 August 2016 on the lower benefit cap, if he will publish the referred estimates of the operational costs of implementing that cap and of providing support to capped claimants.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","69691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715177","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-18","<p>As a large employer we understand the potential impact that any closure or relocation of an office may have. This is why we carefully considered the wider impacts on local communities in reviewing our estate and the sites we intend to keep were identified as part of our longer-term strategy.</p><p> </p><p>The increased use of digital services means that several jobcentres in Liverpool are underutilised; meaning that we are spending money on rent for space that is unused rather than on services and support. Our proposals seek to redress that. However, DWP is retaining a substantial presence in Liverpool and staff will be offered the opportunity to relocate to other parts of DWP wherever possible.</p><p> </p><p>We are recruiting and expect to have more Work Coaches in March 2018 compared to today.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-04-18T16:27:52.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715177/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715177/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715177/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-29","Employment: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect on levels of employment in Liverpool of the announced closure of jobcentres and other offices of his Department's estate; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","69692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715178","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-18","<p>Estimated savings for Removal of the Spare Room Subsidy were published at Budget 2013 as follows:</p><p> </p><p>2013/14 - £465 million</p><p>2014/15 - £465 million</p><p>2015/16 - £465 million</p><p>2016/17 - £470 million</p><p>2017/18 - £470 million</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","69695","2017-04-18T14:06:41.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715178/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715178/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715178/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-29","Housing Benefit: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the savings to his Department arising from the application of the under-occupancy penalty in each of the last four financial years.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","69693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715179","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-18","<p>Estimated savings for Removal of the Spare Room Subsidy were published at Budget 2013 as follows:</p><p> </p><p>2013/14 - £465 million</p><p>2014/15 - £465 million</p><p>2015/16 - £465 million</p><p>2016/17 - £470 million</p><p>2017/18 - £470 million</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","69693","2017-04-18T14:06:41.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715179/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715179/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-29","Housing Benefit: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the savings to his Department arising from the application of the under-occupancy penalty in the current financial year and each of the next three financial years.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","69695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715180","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-24","<p>Once Universal Credit is fully rolled out and claimants have been successfully migrated from their previous benefits in accordance with our published plan, existing systems will be decommissioned if they have no further utility. However, the majority of the legacy benefit IT systems also support provision of other benefits and may therefore have a life beyond that of the full introduction of Universal Credit.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-04-24T15:27:57.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715180/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715180/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715180/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-29","Social Security Benefits: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when his Department plans to close down the IT systems for legacy benefits after the roll-out of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","69738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715181","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-19","<p>The Government wants all disabled people and people with a long term health condition to have the opportunity to work and share in the economic and health benefits that appropriate work can bring. That is why we published ‘Improving Lives the Work, Health and Disability Green Paper’ setting out the action we plan to take and starting a far-reaching, national debate on what more we can do to ensure everyone, including people with musculoskeletal conditions, is supported to reach their full potential.</p><p> </p><p>During our three-month consultation on the Green Paper we heard from a wide range of stakeholders, including organisations who work with and represent people with a wide range of musculoskeletal conditions. We are now taking stock of what we have heard and will then be setting out our next steps for the agenda.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-04-19T11:21:48.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715181/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715181/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715181/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-29","Employment: Musculoskeletal Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans to further consult people with musculoskeletal conditions following the conclusion of the Improving Lives Disability Employment consultation.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","69681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715182","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-18","<p>The information is not held.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-04-18T15:25:15.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715182/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715182/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715182/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-29","Social Security Benefits: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many mandatory reconsideration request decisions made by his Department have been overturned by HM Courts and Tribunals Service since the introduction of that process.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","69684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715183","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-18","<p>The Access to Work Hidden Impairments Speciality team is already able to award funding for specialist support for people on the autistic spectrum.</p><p> </p><p>Access to Work is a discretionary grant award which provides a contribution towards disability related extra costs in the workplace above the level of reasonable adjustments. The scheme funds a wide variety of solutions appropriate to each person’s individual circumstances, on a case by case basis, including:</p><ul><li>Specialist assessments</li><li>Specialist support workers</li><li>Travel to work support</li><li>Autism awareness training for colleagues to combat stigma and workplace bullying</li><li>Innovative technological solutions, such as smartphone apps.</li></ul>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-04-18T14:59:27.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715183/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715183/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715183/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-29","Access to Work Programme: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that the Access to Work Hidden Impairments Specialist Team is able to refer people to specialist autism-specific support.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","69690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715184","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-18","<p>Data on the number of Personal Independence Payment (PIP) claims cleared, by a range of breakdowns including age, the clearance type and whether the claim was a new claim or a Disability Living Allowance to PIP reassessment claim, is available using Stat-Xplore: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>. Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a>.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-04-18T15:15:22.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715184/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715184/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715184/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-29","Personal Independence Payment: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many 16-year olds who were previously in receipt of disability living allowance have had their application for personal independence payments rejected in the last year.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","69715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715185","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-18","<p>The Department does not routinely collect information on the numbers of people who have had to return a Motability vehicle. Also, the Department does not have data available on the numbers who have leased a vehicle under the Motability scheme by year and parliamentary constituency. As the information requested is not readily available, it could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Motability is an independent charitable organisation that is wholly responsible for the administration of the Motability scheme, including collating its own management information. Questions relating to this aspect of the scheme’s operation should be directed to Motability itself.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-04-18T14:53:54.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715185/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715185/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715185/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-29","Motability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on the number of people in (a) Batley and Spen constituency, (b) West Yorkshire and (c) England who have had a Government-funded leased Motability car removed from their possession in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","69687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715186","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-18","<p>This policy change had no impact on Housing Benefit claimants receiving another income-related benefit, such as income-related Employment and Support Allowance, income-based Jobseeker’s Allowance, Income Support or the guarantee element of Pension Credit, which “passports” claimants onto full eligible Housing Benefit.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-04-18T15:40:27.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715186/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715186/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715186/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-29","Family Premium: Liverpool City Region","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of the removal of family premium for new claimants on families with one or more disabled members in (a) Garston and Halewood constituency and (b) Liverpool City Region.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","69847"
