"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715201","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department of Business Energy and Industrial Strategy was formed in July 2016 and its Annual Report to Parliament will include all relevant losses since its formation. Currently, there are no losses to be reported. Any losses will be assessed and responded to individually and on a case by case basis with all possible mitigating actions being taken and in full compliance of our legal and other responsibilities.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-04-24T15:36:52.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715201/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715201/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-29","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many (a) official and (b) official sensitive documents have been recorded as lost by his Department since 8 May 2015.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","69811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715202","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>In taking the decision to grant development consent for the Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon in June 2015, my right hon. Friend the then Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change considered and reviewed the environmental impact assessment for the project. The Secretary of State's consideration was informed by the Planning Inspectorate`s Report on the application for development consent and other relevant information, including environmental information provided by the developer and other parties.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-04-24T12:56:23.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715202/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715202/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-29","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether a review has been carried out of the environmental impact assessment of the Swansea Bay tidal lagoon; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","69793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715203","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Britain Israel Research and Academic Exchange Partnership (BIRAX) is a £10 million initiative supported by the UK Government in Israel. The latest initiative provides research to develop cures for some of the world’s most dreadful diseases.</p><p>Funding is provided from both nations by medical research foundations, charitable trusts, and philanthropists.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-04-24T15:40:08.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715203/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715203/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-29","Research: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what funding his Department allocates to the Britain Israel Research and Academic Exchange Partnership.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","69856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715204","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>(1) The budget and net cost of the Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI) schemes in Great Britain are set out below. The Non-domestic RHI started in November 2011 and the Domestic RHI was launched in April 2014.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Budget*</strong></p></td><td><p>£56m</p></td><td><p>£70m</p></td><td><p>£251m</p></td><td><p>£424m</p></td><td><p>£430m</p></td><td><p>£640m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Subsidy cost</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Non-domestic</em></p></td><td><p><em>£1m</em></p></td><td><p><em>£16m</em></p></td><td><p><em>£54m</em></p></td><td><p><em>£149m</em></p></td><td><p><em>£298m</em></p></td><td><p><em>£459m</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Domestic</em></p></td><td><p><em>-</em></p></td><td><p><em>-</em></p></td><td><p><em>-</em></p></td><td><p><em>£23m</em></p></td><td><p><em>£77m</em></p></td><td><p><em>£91m</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Programme cost**</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Non-domestic</em></p></td><td><p><em>£5m</em></p></td><td><p><em>£5m</em></p></td><td><p><em>£7m</em></p></td><td><p><em>£8m</em></p></td><td><p><em>£7m</em></p></td><td><p><em>£6m</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Domestic</em></p></td><td><p><em>-</em></p></td><td><p><em>-</em></p></td><td><p><em>£5m</em></p></td><td><p><em>£7m</em></p></td><td><p><em>£5m</em></p></td><td><p><em>£4m</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total cost</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£6m</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£21m</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£66m</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£187m</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£387m</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£560m</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Data to end-Feb 2017. All figures rounded to nearest £1m.</p><p>* Budget is for subsidy payments only</p><p>**Programme costs include scheme development and administration costs</p><p>(2) A budget cap was introduced to the RHI in Spring 2016, so the schemes can be closed to new applicants if the annual budgets are at risk of being exceeded.</p><p>(3) The RHI schemes are evaluated regularly. The results of previous evaluations are available here:-</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/collections/renewable-heat-incentive-evaluation" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/collections/renewable-heat-incentive-evaluation</a></p><p>(4) The government reviews the cost of wood pellets as part of periodic reviews of RHI tariffs. This was last done in 2016 as part of the RHI reforms which will be implemented this year. The share of imported wood pellets used by RHI participants is not known.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-04-24T15:37:49.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715204/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715204/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-29","Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the net cost to the public purse was of the (a) domestic and (b) non-domestic consumer Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI) scheme in Great Britain in each year since 2012; and what the budget is for subsidy payments to existing and future participants in those schemes in each year between 2007 and 2012; what assessment he has made of the need for a cap on the RHI schemes' overall expenditure; and if he will undertake a review of the (i) efficacy of such schemes and (b) costs of importing wood pellets.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","69876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715205","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-24","<p>If an employer provides work-related training to an employee it is tax and National Insurance contributions free.</p><p> </p><p>The apprenticeship levy was launched on 6 April 2017. It will help to reverse the trend of employers’ underinvesting in training and put control of funding for apprenticeships in employers’ hands. Employers have already developed new apprenticeships standards in aviation which include Airside Ground Specialist and Aviation Operations Manager, with the Commercial Airline Pilot standard currently in development.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-04-24T11:59:25.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715205/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715205/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-29","Aviation: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will assess the potential merits of creating a levy or tax-free training scheme for general aviation on the condition that pilots qualifying through such a scheme must volunteer for charitable purposes such as air ambulances and civil air patrols.","false","Biography information for Lord Davies of Gower","Gower","Byron Davies","69870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715206","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>The budget for the Employment Agency Standards inspectorate was £0.5m for 2016-17.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-04-24T14:45:37.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715206/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715206/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-29","Employment Agency Standards Inspectorate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the budget of the Employment Agencies Inspectorate was for 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","69881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715207","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-18","<p>The Renewables Obligation (RO) and small-scale Feed in Tariffs (FIT) schemes support the generation of renewable electricity and are funded from levies on electricity supply.</p><p> </p><p>Over the past 12 months the government has provided over £190m in compensation payments to eligible businesses for the indirect costs of the Renewables Obligation (RO) and small scale Feed in Tariffs (FIT) schemes. Of this we have paid over £54m to the steel sector.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-04-18T12:46:03.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715207/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715207/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-29","Energy Intensive Industries: Feed-in Tariffs and Renewables Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much public funding has been provided to (a) energy intensive industries and (b) UK steel producers under the Renewables Obligation and Feed-in Tariff schemes in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","69716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715208","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-19","<p>The government continues to work closely with Thomas Cook and the rest of the industry on the revising of consumer protections, including the Package Travel Directive, which will improve the safety of tourists at home and abroad.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-04-19T12:08:42.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715208/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715208/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-29","Tour Operators","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that travel companies comply with the recommendations of the 2015 independent inquiry into customer health, safety, welfare, relations and crisis management of Thomas Cook.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","69706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715209","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-21","<p>The current contracted delivery from the projects within the Superfast Broadband Programme is available on the DCMS website at <a href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1Hs00bNsyRV1WoOt-fow3rsNXzpcKg26AsOWvk1bvJRk/edit#gid=1411146266" target="_blank">https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1Hs00bNsyRV1WoOt-fow3rsNXzpcKg26AsOWvk1bvJRk/edit#gid=1411146266</a>.</p><p>Information from suppliers on their commercial plans has been provided to BDUK on an in-confidence basis.</p><p>We are on track to meet the 95% target by December 2017. Recent Thinkbroadband figures shown 92.8% of premises already have access to superfast broadband.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-04-21T11:15:53.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715209/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715209/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-29","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 23 March 2017 to Question 68607, if she will publish all evidence considered by her Department which indicates that superfast broadband in the UK is (a) on and (b) not on track to reach 95 per cent of UK premises by December 2017; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","69688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715210","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government is aware that doorstep selling can be regarded as a nuisance but it is a legitimate form of trading, provided all the legislation regulating the practice is observed.</p><p>The Government has no plans to regulate further in this area; the unfair trading or criminal activities of rogue traders are already subject to consumer protection and other criminal statues, and the enforcement authorities have adequate powers to see that the law is applied where there is evidence of wrong-doing.</p><p>The need or case for setting up No Cold Calling Zones is a local matter.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-04-24T09:08:07.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715210/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715210/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-29","Direct Selling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if his Department will take steps to encourage local communities to set up no cold calling zones.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","69670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715211","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government has made no assessment of the potential impact of super-critical coal plants on carbon dioxide emissions.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-04-24T08:43:22.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715211/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715211/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-29","Coal Fired Power Stations: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the potential reduction in carbon dioxide emissions of replacing all coal plants which are over 25-years old with modern super-critical coal plants.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","69671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715212","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-18","<p>As the provision of its post office branches is the responsibility of Post Office Limited, the Department does not hold this information.</p><p> </p><p>I have asked Paula Vennells, the Chief Executive of Post Office Limited, to write to the Hon Member on this matter and provide the information requested. A copy of her reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-04-18T12:41:41.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715212/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715212/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-29","Post Offices: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what information his Department holds on how many and which post offices were subject to temporary closure in (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2012-13, (d) 2013-14, (e) 2014-15, (f) 2015-16 and (g) 2016-17; and what the length of the temporary closure was in each such case.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","69763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715213","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Nuclear Decommissioning Authority publishes the amount spent on decommissioning Sellafield in its Annual Report and Accounts. It also publishes a more detailed figure on the cost of decommissioning the UK’s nuclear sites in the Nuclear Provision section of its website.</p><p> </p><p>The total estimated cost for decommissioning the Sellafield site is £88 billion on an undiscounted basis.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-04-24T14:57:36.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715213/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715213/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-29","Sellafield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will publish the total lifetime cost of the Sellafield nuclear waste plant in Cumbria.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","69841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715214","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Two management contracts have been terminated early by the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority (NDA) in the last five years. These are the Parent Body Agreement with Nuclear Management Partners and the Management and Operation Contract with Sellafield Limited. These cancellations formed part of the process of turning Sellafield Limited into a subsidiary of the NDA which came into effect on 1 April 2016.</p><p> </p><p>On 27 March 2017, my Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy announced in Parliament that the NDA intends to terminate the Parent Body Agreement with Cavendish Fluor Partnership for the management of Magnox sites.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-04-24T14:47:17.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715214/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715214/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-29","Nuclear Decommissioning Authority: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many management contracts placed by the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority have been cancelled early in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","69842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715215","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government supports initiatives to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and move to low carbon forms of electricity generation. We see a move away from the use of coal, the most carbon intensive of fuels, as an essential part of this.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-04-24T10:22:33.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715215/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715215/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-29","Coal Fired Power Stations: India","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if his Department will make an assessment of the potential contribution by UK businesses to the Indian Government's plan to replace all coal plants over 25-years old with super-critical coal plants.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","69683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715216","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-18","<p>Over the last six months Department for International Trade, Ministers and senior officials have visited Singapore and Malaysia to discuss and reaffirm our strong bilateral economic and trade relationships, including a refresh of our Economic and Business Partnership with Singapore and promoting trade and investment opportunities with both countries. Singapore, Malaysia and the wider SE Asia region offer substantial opportunities to UK companies. The Department has identified high value opportunities in aerospace, defence and security, transport infrastructure (particularly rail), education and technology sectors, with strong demand for financial and business services. Officials will continue to evaluate opportunities in healthcare, renewables and other sectors as they emerge.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-04-18T15:48:41.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715216/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715216/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-29","Trade: South East Asia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions his Department has had with the governments of Singapore and Malaysia on future investment and trade deals; and what assessment he has made of the opportunities available to UK businesses in those countries.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","69855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715217","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-18","None.","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-04-18T12:24:59.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715217/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715217/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-29","Adam Werritty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many times he has met Mr Adam Werritty since his Department was established.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","69899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715218","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-24","<p>The information requested is not held centrally. All losses are assessed and responded to individually and on a case by case basis with all possible mitigating actions being taken and in full compliance of our legal and other responsibilities.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-04-24T10:34:18.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715218/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715218/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-29","Department for International Trade: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many (a) official and (b) official sensitive documents have been recorded as lost by his Department since 8 May 2015.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","69824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715219","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-24","<p>Since the formation of the Department no OFFICIAL or OFFICIAL SENSITIVE documents have been recorded as lost.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-04-24T11:03:01.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715219/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715219/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-29","Department for Exiting the European Union: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many (a) official and (b) official sensitive documents have been recorded as lost by his Department since it was established.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","69819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715220","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-18","<p>HM Treasury is responsible to Parliament for the control of public resources – this includes overall responsibility for ensuring good value for money and setting departmental budgets. This responsibility remains as we prepare to leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>However, to ensure those closest to the decisions have the authority to manage public money efficiently and effectively, departments have a certain level of autonomy over expenditure which is not novel, contentious or repercussive.</p><p> </p><p>Therefore, whilst HM Treasury has oversight of policies with significant spending implications, the Treasury will not monitor each individual cost incurred to prepare for EU Exit, including those relating to the Civil Service. This treatment is in line with the spending framework applied to all other expenditure.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-04-18T15:16:23.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715220/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715220/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-29","Civil Service","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the (a) impact on and (b) additional cost to the Civil Service of negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","69717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715292","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-18","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service does not hold this information centrally for First-tier Tribunals as a whole and this information could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-04-18T11:05:59.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715292/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/715292/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-29","First-tier Tribunal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average time period is between the submission of an appeal to the First-tier Tribunal and the hearing date.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","69685"
