"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714517","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-18","<p>This is a devolved matter for the Welsh Government.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-18T10:23:46.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714517/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714517/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714517/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-28","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether an Environmental Impact Assessment has been carried out on the effect of sediment movements along the Severn Estuary following the development of the Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","69569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714518","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-04","<p>Yemen is one of the most serious humanitarian crises in the world. I regularly discuss the humanitarian situation and the risk of famine in Yemen with a wide range of interlocutors including the UN, international partners, Government of Yemen and humanitarian organisations. I most recently raised this with Saudi counterparts on Wednesday 29 March when I met with General Assiri, Advisor to the Saudi Defence Minister and Spokesman on the Saudi-led Coalition in Yemen.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-04T14:38:56.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714518/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714518/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714518/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Yemen: Famine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Saudi Arabian counterparts on the potential famine in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Mr Gavin Shuker","Luton South","Mr Gavin Shuker","69614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714519","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-05","<p>​We remain deeply concerned about human rights violations in Burma. I raised our concerns when I met the Burmese Minister of State for Foreign Affairs, U Kyaw Tin, on 27 February at the Human Rights Council in Geneva. During his visit to Burma in January, the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), also raised similar concerns with State Counsellor Daw Aung San Suu Kyi as well as military-appointed government ministers. When the Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon. Baroness Anelay of St Johns visited Burma last November, she specifically raised the issue of sexual violence with the Burmese Minister of Defence, where she pressed him to handle allegations of sexual violence against women in a thorough and transparent manner.</p><p>The question of whether any crimes under international law have occurred in Burma is a matter for judicial decision, rather than for governments to determine. Our objective remains to end all violations of human rights in Burma, including conflict-related sexual violence.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-04-05T12:57:03.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714519/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714519/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714519/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Burma: Crimes against Humanity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment his Department has made of potential crimes against humanity, including mass sexual violence, in Myanmar.","false","Biography information for Mr Gavin Shuker","Luton South","Mr Gavin Shuker","69618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714520","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-04","<p>We are deeply concerned by the fuel shortages in Gaza and the serious impact on the humanitarian situation, including by disrupting the delivery of basic services and undermining already vulnerable livelihoods. Addressing Gaza’s energy shortfall is critical. We are in regular discussion with the Palestinian Authority, as well as with the Government of Israel, on this topic to encourage improved coordination and an increase in energy supplies.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-04T14:58:53.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714520/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714520/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714520/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Gaza: Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the Palestinian authorities on fuel shortages in Gaza.","false","Biography information for Mr Gavin Shuker","Luton South","Mr Gavin Shuker","69615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714521","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-05","<p>Advancing human rights - including the right to freedom of religion and belief (FoRB) - is embedded across the work of our diplomats. In order to enhance the capabilities of staff working to promote FoRB in their country context, the FCO issued a revised toolkit in October 2016. This coincided with our London Conference on FoRB and Countering Violent Extremism, which was attended by a number of country desk officers. The FCO also routinely provides training and seminars to increase religious literacy amongst staff.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-04-05T12:59:47.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714521/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714521/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714521/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what guidance has been given to country desk officers on incorporating an understanding of freedom of religion or belief in their work.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","69539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714522","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-04","<p>The Foreign Secretary discussed a range of foreign policy issues, including the Middle East Peace Process, with the US administration during his visit to Washington on 21 and 22 March.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-04T14:32:31.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714522/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714522/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714522/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","USA: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the US Administration on the potential move of the US Embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.","false","Biography information for Mr Gavin Shuker","Luton South","Mr Gavin Shuker","69381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714523","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-04","<p>Syria has been allocated £64.8million by the Conflict Stability and Security Fund for 2016-17.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-04T14:35:08.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714523/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714523/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714523/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Syria: Conflict, Stability and Security Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the Answer of 18 December 2015 to Question 19719, how much has been allocated to Syria under the Conflict, Stability and Security Fund in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","69382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714524","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-05","<p>In line with the normal process for accepting gifts, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and Buckingham Palace discussed the offer. As this gift was officially supported by the Georgian Government, it was graciously accepted as being in the spirit of the good relations between two close allies.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-04-05T15:37:06.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714524/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714524/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714524/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Monarchy: Official Gifts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions his Department has had with Buckingham Palace on the gift of a gold chain from the alleged Crown Prince Davit of Georgia.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","69497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714525","Department for International Development","false","2017-04-05","<p>In Syria, we deliver basic governance by supporting local councils in moderate opposition areas to deliver basic services in response to needs identified by their communities. In 2016, UK support helped local councils provide over 2.3 million Syrians with improved infrastructure; including new roads, electricity grids and waste collection services.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-04-05T15:38:22.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714525/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714525/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714525/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-28","Syria: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to the Answer of 18 December 2015 to Question 19719, on Syria, what progress her Department has made in delivering basic governance in Syria since 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","69511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714526","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>Further to my answers of 20 March 2017 (PQ 67806 and PQ 67810), the British Embassy in Kabul has approximately 160 local staff, many of whom speak Dari or Pashto as their native language. We also have a small number of UK-based roles in Kabul where we have trained job holders to speak Dari or Pashto. We are not able to disclose exact figures for operational reasons.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-04-18T14:00:06.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714526/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714526/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714526/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","British Embassy Kabul: Pashto and Persian Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answers of 20 March 2017 to Questions 67806 and 67810, how many diplomats and members of staff based at the UK Embassy in Kabul are UK nationals and are fluent in (a) Dari and (b) Pashto.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","69646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714527","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>The UK is playing a leading role in the response to the current drought affecting several countries across Sub-Saharan Africa. We will continue – bilaterally, and through the UN and the EU – to press partners to urgently step up their support. On 23 March the Foreign Secretary chaired UN Security Council briefings on Somalia and South Sudan, urging partners to support the relief efforts, and to unify their support behind the UN, African Union, and regional governments in addressing the roots of humanitarian crises and displacement, as well as promoting peace and prosperity in the region.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-18T13:49:35.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714527/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714527/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714527/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Sub-Saharan Africa: Droughts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to UN officials on drought and population movement in sub-Saharan Africa.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","69651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714528","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-04","<p>The Foreign Secretary discusses the situation in Syria and the Global Coalition's action against Daesh on a regular basis with US colleagues. He did so most recently during a visit to Washington from 21 to 22 March. As part of the Global Coalition, the UK is clear that while no military operations come without risk, the RAF takes all steps necessary to minimise the risk of causing civilian causalities.</p><p>We are aware of reports of civilian casualties allegedly caused by unilateral US action against Al Qaida targets in northern Syria. We welcome the US undertaking to investigate these reports.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-04T14:40:58.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714528/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714528/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714528/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has had recent discussions with his US counterpart on civilian casualties as a result of US airstrikes in Syria.","false","Biography information for Mr Gavin Shuker","Luton South","Mr Gavin Shuker","69624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714529","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-05","<p>​We regularly receive reports and updates from non-government organisations (NGOs) covering a wide range of human rights issues in China. For example, I hosted a roundtable in October 2016 with a range of NGOs working in this area to hear their opinions and analysis firsthand. Among other human rights issues, we have on occasion received reports that individuals from certain religious and ethnic minority groups may have had their organs removed after they have passed away without their or their families consent. My officials continue to scrutinise any new evidence presented.</p><p>We continue to raise the issue of restrictions on religious freedoms and discrimination against ethnic minorities in China, most recently in our statement to the UN Human Rights Council on 14 March 2017.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-04-05T12:58:09.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714529/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714529/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714529/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","China: Minority Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports his Department has received on the detention of Uyghur, Tibetan and Christian people in China related to the practice of organ harvesting.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","69416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714530","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-04","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office engaged with the Federal Government of Somalia and electoral authorities throughout the recent parliamentary and presidential electoral process, emphasising the importance of it being transparent, credible and safe; and that commitments to make the process more inclusive, including increasing female representation, were respected. The recent electoral process should be seen as a stepping stone to one person one vote elections in four years time.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-04T14:36:59.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714530/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714530/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714530/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Somalia: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions his Department has had with the Somalian Government on the recent presidential elections in that country.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","69417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714531","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-05","<p>​We are aware of some media reports of North Korean defectors in the Russian Federation being sent back to North Korea.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-04-05T12:55:39.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714531/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714531/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714531/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","North Korea: Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports the Government has received on North Korean defectors in Russia being sent back to North Korea.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","69418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714532","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-03","<p>The Government recognises the vital role local staff, including interpreters, played in operations in Afghanistan, and its debt of gratitude to them. As part of that, we have a permanent expert team based in Kabul to investigate claims from local staff who believe their safety is threatened as a result of their work with the UK. They assist with security advice, relocations to safe areas within Afghanistan and, where necessary, relocation to the UK.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-04-03T14:06:25.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714532/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714532/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714532/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-03-28","Afghanistan: Interpreters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps the Government is taking to ensure the safety in Afghanistan of Afghan interpreters who previously worked for the Government.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","69419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714533","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>I refer the hon. Member to my answer of 30 March 2017 (PQ 68841).</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-18T13:44:32.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714533/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714533/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714533/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Israel: Entry Clearances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has made to the Israeli Government on the effect of recent law changes on the ability of UK citizens to support the rights of the Palestinian people.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","69464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714534","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>​The Government is acutely aware of the need to learn lessons from other countries' experiences of hostile cyber activity and information operations. This is factored into our National Cyber Security Strategy, the latest version of which was published in November 2016 and can be found on gov.uk. <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-cyber-security-strategy-2016-to-2021" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-cyber-security-strategy-2016-to-2021</a></p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-04-18T14:26:39.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714534/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714534/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714534/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Ukraine: Electronic Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to learn from the cyber and information warfare experienced in Ukraine over the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","69474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714535","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>The UK Government continues to closely monitor the human rights situation in Cameroon. Our High Commissioner has raised our concerns directly with the President Biya on a number of recent occasions. We call on Cameroon to uphold its human rights obligations and to take a lead in resolving the current tensions through a broad-based dialogue.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-18T13:46:57.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714535/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714535/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714535/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Cameroon: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 22 February 2017 to Question 64298, what recent progress he has made in discussions with his counterparts in the Government of Cameroon on the arrest, detention and violent treatment of activists in that country.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","69468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714536","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>​Legal issues in Hong Kong are a matter for the relevant authorities in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region. We have therefore not raised the issue with the Chinese Government. We are aware of concerns about the timing of the charging of nine activists involved in the 2014 protests. The British Consulate General in Hong Kong has raised the issue with the Department for Justice. Hong Kong's success and stability depend on its high degree of autonomy, independent judiciary and respect for the fundamental rights and freedoms enshrined in the Sino-British Joint Declaration and the Basic Law.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-04-18T13:28:20.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714536/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714536/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714536/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Hong Kong: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with (a) his Chinese counterpart and (b) members of the Hong Kong Government on the charging of nine activists over the 2014 Umbrella Revolution protests.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","69470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714537","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>NHS Improvement is resourced to undertake a number of functions, which include working with National Health Service providers to ensure that due diligence processes are completed in a timely and effective manner. In the case of the Liverpool Community Health contract, the publication of the Care Quality Commission report into Bridgewater Community Healthcare NHS Foundation Trust led to a pause in the transaction.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","69438 ; 69439 ; 69495","2017-04-05T12:36:37.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714537/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714537/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714537/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","NHS Improvement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of funding allocated to NHS Improvement to undertake appropriate due diligence on NHS contracts.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","69440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714538","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>The legal framework is contained in directions from the Secretary of State to the NHS Trust Development Authority. The procurement process did not trigger the Public Contract Regulations and it was instead structured as a provider to provider transaction.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","69437","2017-04-05T12:45:11.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714538/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714538/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714538/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Community Health Services: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, under which NHS rules the process which awarded Bridgewater NHS Trust the contract to deliver Liverpool Community services was run; and what the legal framework was underpinning that decision-making process.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","69441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714539","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>The current community pharmacy contractual framework and system of payments dates from 2005/06, with remuneration under those arrangements set out in the table below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year</p></td><td><p>Remuneration budget (£ billion)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005/06</p></td><td><p>1.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/07</p></td><td><p>1.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/08</p></td><td><p>1.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>2.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>2.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2.7</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The budget figures in the table only cover essential and advanced services, as commissioned centrally under the community pharmacy contractual framework. Community pharmacies are also commissioned locally to provide services, originally by primary care trusts and more recently by NHS England, clinical commissioning groups and local authorities. Information on the level of funding received by community pharmacies for those locally commissioned services is not held centrally.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-05T10:21:25.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714539/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714539/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714539/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Pharmacy: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much funding was allocated by the Government to pharmacies in each year from 1997-98 to 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Michael Dugher","Barnsley East","Michael Dugher","69455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714540","Department of Health","false","2017-04-18","<p>NHS England currently assesses clinical commissioning groups’ (CCGs) governance arrangements through two indicators in the leadership domain of the 2016/17 CCG Improvement and Assessment Framework.</p><p> </p><p>This features a quality of leadership indicator, which reviews the CCG’s governance framework to ensure that responsibilities are clear, regular review is built in, and that quality, performance, and finance risks are understood and managed. Characteristics of strong financial leadership are particularly highlighted.</p><p> </p><p>A probity and corporate governance indicator focuses on conflicts of interest and assesses compliance with a number of requirements of the managing conflicts of interest revised statutory guidance for CCGs, published on 28 June 2016, based on sections 14O and 14Z8 of the NHS Act 2006 (as amended). A requirement of the strengthened guidance is for CCGs to include an annual audit of conflicts of interest within their internal audit plan and to include the findings of this audit within their annual end of year governance statement.</p><p>NHS England is supported by legislation in exercising formal powers of direction, as laid out in section 14Z21 of the NHS Act 2006 (as amended), if it is satisfied that a CCG is failing or is at risk of failing to discharge its functions. This may be applicable in cases of serious or systemic governance failure.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-18T08:39:02.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714540/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714540/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714540/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Clinical Commissioning Groups: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what performance and regulatory framework NHS England operates to ensure that clinical commissioning groups meet standards of good governance; and what powers NHS England has to take action where there are instances of governance failures falling below the standard set in those frameworks.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","69475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714541","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>The new Royal Hospital in Liverpool was expected to admit its first patients in the summer of 2017. The projected handover from the contractor to the Trust, following completion of the construction works, was scheduled to be in March 2017. It is then standard to allow a further three months for the Trust to carry out clinical commissioning and for relocation of services before the Hospital is ready to admit patients for treatment. Unfortunately the construction work has been subject to significant delay.</p><p> </p><p>The reasons for delays to the construction timetable have been the discovery of asbestos; issues with using cranes in high winds; a delay in completing a new electrical connection and more recently, the discovery of cracks in some of the concrete beams, for which all remedial work has now been carried out. Clearly, this delay in delivering a new flagship hospital for the people of Liverpool is disappointing. However, we must emphasise that the costs associated with the problems to the new building have to be met by the building contractor and do not fall on the National Health Service. The Trust does not make any payment until the new hospital is finished and is available for use.</p><p> </p><p>Currently the Trust is expecting the contractor to hand over the building at the end of February 2018. The move is then expected to be completed 14 weeks after the handover date.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-05T10:34:51.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714541/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714541/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714541/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Royal Liverpool Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what date is planned for the official opening of the new Royal Hospital Liverpool; whether that date is the originally planned date; and whether any structural problems have been identified within the building.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","69442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714542","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>The Department has asked NHS England to look into the remuneration of non-executive directors at Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group and to write to the hon. Member once their enquiries are completed.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-05T13:05:19.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714542/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714542/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714542/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he plans to publish the findings of the review commissioned by the Prime Minister from NHS England on non-executive salaries in Liverpool.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","69443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714543","Department of Health","false","2017-04-04","<p>NHS England has a statutory duty to conduct an annual performance assessment of every clinical commissioning group (CCG). From 2013-16 this was through the CCG assurance framework. From 2016 this was replaced by the CCG improvement and assessment framework. These frameworks assessed whether CCGs had good governance arrangements.</p><p> </p><p>Liverpool CCG was rated good in the 2015-16 CCG assurance annual assessment. No probity issues have been raised for Liverpool CCG. It has received unqualified opinions in respect of probity and value for money from its external auditors each year.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-04T13:08:44.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714543/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714543/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714543/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Clinical Commissioning Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assurance process has been in place since clinical commissioning groups were established to ensure good governance and probity; and what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of those arrangements in the Liverpool area.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","69446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714544","Department of Health","false","2017-04-04","<p>Patients and patient groups are involved at all stages of the decision making process around the funding of specialised treatments.</p><p> </p><p>Patients are involved in the policy working groups that develop policy propositions, as well the Clinical Reference Groups and National Programmes of Care board which collectively develop policies and which both have patient and public voice members. The Clinical Priorities Advisory Group (CPAG), which makes recommendations around prioritisation, also has an independent lay chair and members. Patients and patient groups can also register as stakeholders and will then be invited to comment on draft policies during stakeholder testing and public consultation. Registered stakeholders are kept informed of progress and are notified when final decisions are made. Patient groups can request a stakeholder surgery with NHS England at any point during the policy development process to raise any issues or concerns they may have.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England ensures that all newly adopted clinical commissioning policies and service specifications are published on its website, and simultaneously cascaded via local commissioning teams to relevant providers and clinical teams. This helps to ensure that patients receive up to date advice on the availability and funding of National Health Service specialised treatments pertinent to them during their clinical consultation.</p><p> </p><p>While the minutes of CPAG are not published, the key information that it used as the basis of its recommendation made on each clinical policy in 2016 was published when the 22 clinical policies went out to public consultation. The methodology used by CPAG to group the policies into five levels has also been published, as have the final recommendations.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has laid out its plans to improve transparency in Specialised Commissioning in its Treasury Minute in response to the 10th Report of the Public Accounts Committee, Session 2016-17, HC397.</p><p>Details of its response can be found at the following address from page 53:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/565426/57448_Cm_9351_Treasury_Minutes_Accessible.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/565426/57448_Cm_9351_Treasury_Minutes_Accessible.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The CPAG is not a decision making body – it makes recommendations to NHS England on clinical priorities. Final decisions are made by the Specialised Services Commissioning Committee and the committee's decisions are reported to the NHS England Board and published as part of the Board Papers.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","69493 ; 69494","2017-04-04T13:38:27.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714544/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714544/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714544/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Medical Treatments: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent discussions he has had with NHS England on improving the way that decisions about the funding of treatments are communicated to patient groups and the public.","false","Biography information for Mark Tami","Alyn and Deeside","Mark Tami","69492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714545","Department of Health","false","2017-04-04","<p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) are independent statutory bodies set out in statute, and as such are responsible for recruiting and selecting their leadership team. The appointment of Accountable Officers by CCGs requires authorisation by NHS England. If as suggested the CCGs seek to create a joint management team with a single Accountable Officer shared across two or three CCGs, this will be subject to NHS England's approval. NHS England’s process for such appointments is set out in guidance published in March 2017.</p><p>There are provisions under section 14G of the NHS Act 2006 (as amended) allowing for mergers of CCGs and there are specific legal factors that NHS England must consider when deciding whether or not to agree the merger.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-04T13:13:44.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714545/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714545/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714545/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Furness Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will ensure that there will be no appointments to a single management board prior to any clinical commissioning group mergers until the situation that resulted in commissioning the Kirkup report has been satisfactorily resolved.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","69436"
