outhwark","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many mental health nurses have been employed by the local NHS trust in Southwark in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","69653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714573","Department of Health","false","2017-04-18","<p>NHS England is leading a review of low value prescription items which are clinically ineffective, unnecessary, unsafe or inappropriate for prescription on the National Health Service, for example, because they can be purchased relatively inexpensively over the counter, often at a lower price than they cost the NHS.</p><p> </p><p>Initially this work will focus on the top 10 areas of low clinical value as identified by NHS Clinical Commissioners through a survey of their member. Areas it will consider will be determined according to where there is evidence of low clinical value and/or where there is significant NHS expenditure.</p><p> </p><p>Although complementary and alternative medicines (CAMs) are still available for individual practitioners to prescribe, many clinical commissioning groups have already issued guidance relating to their availability on the NHS. The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence provides guidance to the NHS on effective treatments that are value for money, and has recommended the use of CAMs in only a limited number of circumstances.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-18T13:33:04.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714573/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714573/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714573/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Homeopathy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if the Government will add homeopathic products and other herbal remedies that have no basis in science to the list of items under review by the NHS.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","69634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714574","Department of Health","false","2017-04-18","<p>At the G8 summit in December 2013, the G8 countries agreed a new international approach to dementia research to realise the ambition to identify a cure or disease modifying therapy by 2025 and to increase collectively and significantly their funding for dementia research.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has doubled research spending on dementia, with a commitment to maintain this level of spending at £60 million a year to 2020, with an ambition for overall spending on research from all sectors to double by 2025. Much of this investment is in research to better understand the nature of dementia, to inform development of future treatments and ways to prevent the onset of the condition.</p><p> </p><p>A key aspiration in the Government’s Challenge on Dementia 2020 is to improve public awareness and understanding of the factors which can increase the risk of developing dementia and of how people can reduce their risk by living more healthily.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England (PHE) has published improved guidance on reducing dementia risk, including ‘Health Matters: A resource for health professionals and local authorities’ that makes the case for action in midlife to promote healthy lifestyles that can reduce the risk of dementia.</p><p> </p><p>PHE also increases awareness of dementia risk reduction through programmes for the public, such as the NHS Health Check.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-18T10:55:27.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714574/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714574/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714574/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Dementia: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department plans to take to work towards the elimination of dementia among senior citizens in the next 20 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","69652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714575","Department of Health","false","2017-04-04","<p>The attached table sets out when the Department agreed each of the projects with the stated recipients listed in the answer to Question 66933 and when each project commenced.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-04T11:58:50.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714575/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714575/answer","PQ69654 attached table.docx","PQ69654 attached table.docx","PQ69654 attached table","PQ69654 attached table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714575/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Department of Health: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 15 March 2017 to Question 66933, on Department of Health: overseas aid, when each of those projects listed in that Answer were agreed with the stated recipients; and when each such project commenced.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","69654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714576","Department of Health","false","2017-04-18","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is the independent body responsible for providing robust, evidence based guidance for the National Health Service on the clinical and cost effectiveness of drugs and other treatments. NICE is currently appraising nivolumab for use in the treatment of relapsed or refractory classical Hodgkin lymphoma. NICE published its draft guidance for consultation on 14 March and stakeholders had until 3 April to comment. NICE currently expects to publish final guidance in July 2017.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-18T13:47:53.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714576/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714576/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714576/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Nivolumab: Hodgkin Lymphoma","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the clinical benefits of nivolumab for patients with relapsed or refractory classical Hodgkin lymphoma.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","69561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714577","Department of Health","false","2017-04-18","<p>NHS Digital has been working with NHS England, the Department, the Advertising Standards Authority and Healthwatch, to improve the information available to the public on dentistry on NHS Choices. The first tranche of improvements went live earlier this month. These included action to encourage practices to regularly update their profiles and, in particular, information on whether the practice is taking on new patients, which now has a mandatory 90 day review cycle. If this information is not updated or verified as still correct within a 90 day period, it will be temporarily removed from the site. Consideration continues to what further action could be taken to ensure information is updated regularly.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-18T10:49:28.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714577/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714577/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714577/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Dental Services: Patient Choice Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make it a requirement that dentistry practices update their information on the NHS Choices website.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","69639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714578","Department of Health","false","2017-04-18","<p>NHS England has advised that there are two main drugs that are currently licensed for the treatment of patients who have failed standard therapies for their Hodgkin lymphoma; brentuximab and nivolumab.</p><p> </p><p>Brentuximab is currently available through the Cancer Drugs Fund for the treatment of patients with relapsed or refractory CD30 positive Hodgkin’s lymphoma. The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is currently appraising brentuximab and expects to publish final guidance in May 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Nivolumab is licensed for patients with Hodgkin lymphoma who have progressed despite an autologous stem cell transplant and who have also received treatment with brentuximab. NICE is currently appraising nivolumab for use in this indication and expects to publish final guidance in July 2017. Nivolumab is not currently funded routinely in this indication.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-18T13:46:18.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714578/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714578/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714578/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Hodgkin Lymphoma","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the availability of treatment options for patients with classical Hodgkin lymphoma whose disease has progressed or not responded to standard of care treatments.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","69562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714579","Department of Health","false","2017-04-04","<p>Sustainability and Transformation Plans are not statutory organisations; instead they represent local organisations coming together to work collectively. The statutory architecture for health and care remains fully in place, as do the existing accountabilities for Chief Executives and Accountable Officers of National Health Service organisations.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-04T13:05:47.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714579/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714579/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714579/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","NHS: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to oral evidence given to the Public Accounts Committee on 27 February 2017, if he will specify the legal status of the new organisations that will be established under NHS England's Sustainability and Transformation Plans; and what duties and powers to plan and provide health services those organisations will have.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","69611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714580","Department of Health","false","2017-04-18","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is an independent body and is responsible for the methods and processes it uses in the development of its guidance, which are developed through extensive engagement with stakeholders and periodically reviewed to ensure they remain appropriate. NICE has been able to recommend a number of drugs for the treatment of blood cancers for small patient populations through its technology appraisal programme.</p><p> </p><p>NICE has not yet published final guidance on the use of nivolumab for the treatment of relapsed or refractory classical Hodgkin lymphoma and stakeholders had until 3 April to comment on NICE’s draft recommendations.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-18T13:44:19.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714580/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714580/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714580/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Nivolumab","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with NICE on that body's decision not to recommend nivolumab for treating relapsed or refractory classical Hodgkin lymphoma and the suitability of methods of appraisal used to assess blood cancer medicines which treat small patient populations.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","69563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714581","Department of Health","false","2017-04-18","<p>Our reforms are about improving services for patients and the public and securing efficiencies and savings. A consequence may be the closure of some pharmacies but that is not our aim.</p><p> </p><p>In the Spending Review the Government re-affirmed the need for the National Health Service to deliver £22 billion in efficiency savings by 2020/21 as set out in the NHS’s own plan, the Five Year Forward View. Community pharmacy is a vital part of the NHS and can play an even greater role. Community pharmacy is a core part of NHS primary care and has an important contribution to make as the NHS rises to these challenges. The Government believes efficiencies can be made without compromising the quality of community pharmacy services including public access to medicines.</p><p> </p><p>Our aim is to ensure that those community pharmacies upon which people depend continue to thrive and so we have a Pharmacy Access Scheme, which will provide more NHS funds to certain pharmacies compared to others, considering factors such as location and the health needs of the local population.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","69395","2017-04-18T14:16:14.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714581/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714581/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714581/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Pharmacy: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many pharmacies he estimates will close in (a) Welwyn Hatfield constituency and (b) England in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","69645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714582","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>The Government has committed £50 million towards setting up a Global Antimicrobial Resistance (AMR) Innovation Fund to increase global investment in AMR. The fund aims to leverage substantial new international investment in AMR research and development for new and repurposed antimicrobials and alternative medicines, rapid diagnostic tests, vaccines and other important technologies, interventions and therapies.</p><p>Professor Dame Sally Davies, the Chief Medical Officer for England and United Kingdom Government adviser, has appointed an expert advisory board to make recommendations on the scope and focus of the investment.</p><p>These discussions are ongoing.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-05T10:00:27.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714582/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714582/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714582/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Antimicrobials: Drug Resistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he expects the Global Antimicrobial Resistance Innovation Fund to be open to research applications for the repurposing of antibiotics.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","69526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714583","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>NHS Improvement and NHS England have no plans to change the national prices for 2017/18 and 2018/19 for photodynamic therapy. However, providers and commissioners can agree to vary national prices where this would be in the best interest of patients. These ‘local variations’ can be agreed in accordance with National Tariff rules on locally-determined prices.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-05T12:37:47.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714583/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714583/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714583/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Cancer: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make it his policy to raise the NHS Improvement tariff for photodynamic therapy to cover the full cost of that procedure; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Pauline Latham","Mid Derbyshire","Pauline Latham","69535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714584","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>The Global Antimicrobial Resistance (AMR) Innovation Fund is a £50 million investment over five years to tackle AMR, with the aim of attracting significant additional investment internationally to stimulate global research. It is not looking at reimbursement models to incentivise the development of new classes of antibiotics or planning to fund pilots at this stage.</p><p>Domestically, the Department is working with the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence and the Association of the British Pharmaceutical Industry to develop a new reimbursement model for antimicrobials, and has secured broad agreement to principles that would permit a model to ‘de-link’ company revenues from sales. The aim of this work is to support good antimicrobial stewardship. Discussions with a number of leading pharmaceutical companies have highlighted challenges in evaluating antimicrobial medicines, and the Department is working closely with industry partners to address these.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-05T10:24:11.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714584/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714584/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714584/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Antimicrobials: Drug Resistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he expects the first pilots of the Global Antimicrobial Resistance Innovation Fund on reimbursement models to incentivise the development of new classes of antibiotics to begin.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","69527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714585","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>Information on the public funding NHS Blood and Transplant received in 2014-15 and 2015-16 can be found within its 2015-16 Annual Report and Accounts.</p><p>The Department has provided funding of £2,000,000 in 2014-15 and £1,325,057 in 2015-16 to the charity Anthony Nolan to support improving the availability of stem cells for patients requiring a transplant from an unrelated donor.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-05T10:06:35.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714585/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714585/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714585/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Anthony Nolan Bone Marrow Trust and NHS Blood and Transplant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much public funding has been provided to (a) NHS Blood and Transplant and (b) Anthony Nolan in each of the two previous financial years.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","69514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714586","Department of Health","false","2017-04-04","<p>In 2010, the Committee on the Medical Effects of Air Pollution (COMEAP) published a statement on the evidence linking air pollution with asthma. The evidence confirmed that exposure to ambient concentrations of air pollutants is associated with an increase in exacerbations of asthma in those who already have the condition. The evidence for air pollution causing new cases of asthma is less clear. However, COMEAP concluded that it is possible that air pollution plays a part in the induction of asthma in some individuals who live near busy roads, particularly roads carrying high numbers of heavy goods vehicles.</p><p> </p><p>No specific assessments of the potential effect of air pollution on incidences of asthma or asthma hospitalisation rates for children or adults living in Greater Manchester have been made. There are no plans for Public Health England to make an assessment of the potential effect of air pollution on incidences of asthma or asthma hospitalisation rates in Greater Manchester.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","69505","2017-04-04T11:49:38.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714586/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714586/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Air Pollution: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of air pollution on (a) incidences of asthma and (b) asthma hospitalisation rates for (i) children and (ii) adults living in Greater Manchester in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","69515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714587","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>No discussions have taken place with Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group on this matter.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Improvement is resourced to undertake a number of functions, which include working with National Health Service providers to ensure that due diligence processes are completed in a timely and effective manner. Quality Impact Assessments and a Financial Assessment were undertaken as part of the pre-assessment process.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-05T12:47:38.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714587/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714587/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714587/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","NHS Improvement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he made of the likely effects of breaking up the former Liverpool Community contract into 13 parts; what discussions he has had with Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group on the potential for that decision to align with a previously agreed joint venture between the Group and Liverpool City Council and Bridgwater; what assessment he has made of the risk of poor governance in decision making; and whether NHS Improvement is sufficiently resourced to take poor decision-making.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","69496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714588","Department of Health","false","2017-04-04","<p>The information requested is in the following table.</p><p> </p><p>Median waiting times (days) of first outpatient appointments for treatment specialties ophthalmology, paediatric ophthalmology, medical ophthalmology optometry, and orthoptics in England for 2015-16</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Treatment Specialty</p></td><td><p>Median Time Waited (days)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ophthalmology</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>41</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Paediatric Ophthalmology</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>56</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Medical Ophthalmology</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>42</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Optometry</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>49</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Orthoptics</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>40</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source:</em> Hospital Episode Statistics, NHS Digital</p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><p>The following codes were used to identify treatment specialties:</p><p>130 - Ophthalmology</p><p>216 - Paediatric Ophthalmology</p><p>460 - Medical ophthalmology</p><p>662 - Optometry</p><p>655 - Orthoptics</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-04T13:44:29.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714588/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714588/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714588/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Outpatients: Attendance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the median waiting time for a first (a) outpatient ophthalmology, (b) paediatric ophthalmology, (c) medical ophthalmology, (d) outpatient optometry and (e) outpatient orthoptic appointment was in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","69487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714589","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>NHS Improvement is resourced to undertake a number of functions, which include working with National Health Service providers to ensure that due diligence processes are completed in a timely and effective manner. In the case of the Liverpool Community Health contract, the publication of the Care Quality Commission report into Bridgewater Community Healthcare NHS Foundation Trust led to a pause in the transaction.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","69439 ; 69440 ; 69495","2017-04-05T12:36:37.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714589/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714589/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714589/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","NHS Improvement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how long NHS Improvement should allow for the due diligence regime once a contract is provided to a new supplier; whether due diligence is completed to a specific deadline; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","69438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714590","Department of Health","false","2017-04-18","<p>No review is due to take place. Following the procurement process local commissioners, comprised of Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group, the local councils and NHS England, took the decision to separate services in the interests of local patients.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-18T09:54:47.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714590/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714590/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714590/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Community Health Services: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will review the decision to break-up the services previously provided by a single block contract by Liverpool Community Health NHS Trust into 13 separate contracts during the recent procurement process; and what the role was of (a) Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group and (b) NHS Improvement in making that original decision.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","69574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714591","Department of Health","false","2017-04-04","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care in England. The CQC has provided the following information in the table below.</p><p> </p><p>Number of active care homes and number of care home beds</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Number of Active Care Homes</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Number of Care Home Beds</p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>Total Number of Active Care Homes</p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>Total Number of Care Home Beds</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Date</p></td><td><p>Nursing Home</p></td><td><p>Residential Home</p></td><td><p>Nursing Home</p></td><td><p>Residential Home</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31 March 2015</p></td><td><p>4,698</p></td><td><p>12,382</p></td><td><p>224,751</p></td><td><p>239,363</p></td><td><p>17,080</p></td><td><p>464,114</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31 March 2016</p></td><td><p>4,643</p></td><td><p>12,122</p></td><td><p>224,853</p></td><td><p>237,182</p></td><td><p>16,765</p></td><td><p>462,035</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>29 March 2017</p></td><td><p>4,504</p></td><td><p>11,890</p></td><td><p>221,188</p></td><td><p>238,765</p></td><td><p>16,394</p></td><td><p>459,953</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p>- A care home with both service types of ‘care home with nursing’ and ‘care home without nursing’ is classified as a nursing home. A residential home is a ‘care home service without nursing’.</p><p>- Care home bed numbers can change over time. The data supplied is based on the number of beds at date of data extraction, or date of the location's de-activation if it is no longer active.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-04T13:50:41.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714591/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714591/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714591/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Care Homes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Answer of 4 March 2016 to Question 29083, how many (a) registered care home and (b) nursing home places there were in (i) 2017, (ii) 2016 and (iii) 2015.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","69386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714592","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>The total number of registered donors on the Anthony Nolan and NHS Stem Cell Registry and the numbers of registered donors from black and minority ethnic backgrounds are reported in the 2016 Anthony Nolan annual report.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-05T10:26:31.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714592/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714592/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714592/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Stem Cells: Donors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Answer of 8 March 2016 to Question 28969, what information his Department holds on the number of (a) people who were registered as stem cell donors with the Anthony Nolan and NHS Stem Cell Registry and (b) such people who were from Black and minority ethnic backgrounds in 2015-16 to date.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","69387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714593","Department of Health","false","2017-04-18","<p>The Department has asked NHS England to look into the remuneration of non-executive directors at Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group and to write to the Honourable Lady once their enquiries are completed.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-18T10:03:27.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714593/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714593/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714593/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Prime Minister's Answer to the Question from the hon. Member for West Lancashire of 22 March 2017, Official Report, column 864, if he will ensure that the review of the remuneration of non-executive directors at Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) includes (a) all members of and (b) an assessment of the governance arrangement for Liverpool CCG; and if he will publish the review.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","69572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714594","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>The following table shows additional funding given to the National Health Service for winter and seasonal resilience between 2011-12 and 2014-15:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Additional Funding</p></td><td><p>Date</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£300 million (winter resilience)</p></td><td><p>January 2012</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£330 million (winter resilience)</p></td><td><p>September 2012</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£400 million (winter resilience)</p></td><td><p>November 2013</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£700 million (winter resilience)</p></td><td><p>Start of the financial year</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£400 million (seasonal resilience)</p></td><td><p>Start of the financial year</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>£400 million (seasonal resilience)</p></td><td><p>Start of the financial year</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-05T12:42:58.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714594/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714594/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714594/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Health Services: Weather","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Answer of 17 November 2015 to Question 902116, how much additional financial support in winter resilience funds the NHS received in each year from 2011-12 to 2016-17; and on what dates in those years that additional support was allocated.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","69388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714595","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>The backlog maintenance cost reported by the National Health Service in total for the last three years is:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2013-14 £ million</p></td><td><p>2014-15 £ million</p></td><td><p>2015-16 £ million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>High risk</p></td><td><p>357</p></td><td><p>458</p></td><td><p>776</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Significant risk</p></td><td><p>1,017</p></td><td><p>1,062</p></td><td><p>1,568</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Moderate risk</p></td><td><p>1,427</p></td><td><p>1,551</p></td><td><p>1,516</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Low risk</p></td><td><p>1,242</p></td><td><p>1,267</p></td><td><p>1,115</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>4,043</p></td><td><p>4,338</p></td><td><p>4,975</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The data for each NHS organisation is attached.</p><p> </p><p>The Department collects data on backlog maintenance annually from NHS trusts through the Estates Returns Information Collection. The data collected has not been amended centrally and its accuracy always remains the responsibility of the NHS organisations concerned.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-05T12:33:21.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714595/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714595/answer","PQ69510 attached table.xls","PQ69510 attached table.xls","PQ69510 attached table ","PQ69510 attached table ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714595/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","NHS: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the cost of backlog maintenance for each level of assessed risk was in the NHS (a) in total and (b) for each NHS organisation in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","69510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714596","Department of Health","false","2017-04-04","<p>On 27 February the chief executives of NHS England and NHS Improvement wrote to Sustainability and Transformation Plans (STP) leaders. They stated the upcoming NHS Delivery Plan will outline the steps NHS England and NHS Improvement will take to help ensure all areas have developed credible implementation plans.</p><p> </p><p>The additional £325 million announced in the Spring Budget will help the STPs with the strongest projects make real progress in improving care for local communities.</p><p> </p><p>This additional resource is solely for use by capital bid projects subject to the usual assurance processes by NHS England and HM Treasury. No decisions have been made regarding the allocation of funds.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-04T13:15:28.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714596/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714596/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714596/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","NHS: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to NHS England's Delivering the Forward View: NHS Planning Guidance 2016-17 to 2020-21, whether additional funding will be made available to the Birmingham and Solihull Sustainability and Transformation Plan from April 2017.","false","Biography information for Ms Gisela Stuart","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Ms Gisela Stuart","69518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714597","Department of Health","false","2017-04-18","<p>The new Royal Hospital in Liverpool was expected to admit its first patients in the summer of 2017. The projected handover from the contractor to the Trust, following completion of the construction works, was scheduled to be in March 2017. It is then standard to allow a further three months for the Trust to carry out clinical commissioning and for relocation of services before the Hospital is ready to admit patients for treatment. Unfortunately the construction work has been subject to significant delay.</p><p> </p><p>The reasons for delays to the construction timetable have been the discovery of asbestos; issues with using cranes in high winds; a delay in completing a new electrical connection and more recently, the discovery of cracks in some of the concrete beams, for which all remedial work has now been carried out. Clearly, this delay in delivering a new flagship hospital for the people of Liverpool is disappointing. However, the costs associated with the problems to the new building have to be met by the building contractor and do not fall on the National Health Service. The trust does not make any payment until the new hospital is finished and is available for use.</p><p> </p><p>Currently the Trust is expecting the contractor to hand over the building at the end of February 2018. The move is then expected to be completed 14 weeks after the handover date.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","69556","2017-04-18T17:18:54.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714597/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714597/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714597/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Royal Liverpool Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the official opening of the Royal Liverpool University Hospital will take place on the originally planned date; whether structural problems with the constructing of buildings have affected that date; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","69555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714598","Department of Health","false","2017-04-18","<p>The new Royal Hospital in Liverpool was expected to admit its first patients in the summer of 2017. The projected handover from the contractor to the Trust, following completion of the construction works, was scheduled to be in March 2017. It is then standard to allow a further three months for the Trust to carry out clinical commissioning and for relocation of services before the Hospital is ready to admit patients for treatment. Unfortunately the construction work has been subject to significant delay.</p><p> </p><p>The reasons for delays to the construction timetable have been the discovery of asbestos; issues with using cranes in high winds; a delay in completing a new electrical connection and more recently, the discovery of cracks in some of the concrete beams, for which all remedial work has now been carried out. Clearly, this delay in delivering a new flagship hospital for the people of Liverpool is disappointing. However, the costs associated with the problems to the new building have to be met by the building contractor and do not fall on the National Health Service. The trust does not make any payment until the new hospital is finished and is available for use.</p><p> </p><p>Currently the Trust is expecting the contractor to hand over the building at the end of February 2018. The move is then expected to be completed 14 weeks after the handover date.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","69555","2017-04-18T17:18:54.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714598/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714598/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714598/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Royal Liverpool Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the anticipated date for the handover of the new buildings to Royal Liverpool and Broadgreen University NHS Trust is.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","69556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714599","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>This Government is committed to improving maternity and neonatal care. In November 2015 my Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State announced a national ambition to halve the number of neonatal deaths, stillbirths, maternal deaths and brain injuries occurring during or soon after birth by 2030. The Department is working closely with NHS England to make progress on the ambition and implement the NHS England led Maternity Transformation Programme, a programme set up to deliver the National Maternity Review’s recommendations, outlined in the report Better Births.</p><p> </p><p>The Better Births publication set out the vision for maternity services across England. It also outlined that a dedicated review of neonatal services should be taken forward in light of the overall maternity review findings. Within that context, and linked to NHS England’s Maternity Transformation Programme, the Neonatal Critical Care Clinical Reference Group, chaired by Professor Neil Marlow, is carrying out a review of neonatal services. That review is ongoing and will report in September 2017 but it has acknowledged that adequate support and facilities for parents are integral to the provision of centred care.</p><p> </p><p>The review has completed its data gathering stage and will be working with Bliss and other stakeholders to develop recommendations for service improvement, including the support and facilities for parents.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-05T12:39:52.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714599/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714599/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714599/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Baby Care Units","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the report by Bliss, entitled Neonatal care and admissions variation in the provisions for the parents of babies receiving neonatal care; and if he will take steps to reduce those variations.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","69577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714600","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>Potential students have a range of reasons for making the choices they do regarding courses to apply for.</p><p> </p><p>At this stage of the application cycle, based on the data the Universities and Colleges Admissions Service published on 2 February 2017, Health Education England is confident that the National Health Service will be able to fill the number of 2017/18 pre-registration nursing degree training places in England. Entry to nursing, midwifery and allied health profession remains extremely competitive with a ratio from applications this January of nearly two applicants per place, this shows that there is a strong market for students who want to study high-quality nursing degree.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to monitoring the reforms throughout the application process and in doing so is working with Health Education England, Universities UK and the Council of Deans of Health to ensure that students are aware of the benefits of studying to become a nurse.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-05T12:41:28.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714600/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714600/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714600/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the 23 per cent decline in UCAS applications for nursing degrees in 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","69616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714601","Department of Health","false","2017-04-18","<p>The NHS Pay Review Body does not have a budget. NHS Pay Review Body member expenses and the costs of member recruitment are covered by the Department of Health budget, (£27,400 so far in 2016-17). The secretariat is provided by the Office of Manpower Economics (OME, part of the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy).</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-18T10:04:43.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714601/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714601/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714601/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","NHS Pay Review Body","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the annual budget is of the NHS Pay Review Body.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","69550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714602","Home Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>The Department does not hold that information. Responsibility for landlord insurance is a matter for the Service Providers to address via their individual arrangements with their Sub-Contractors and/or Landlords.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-04-18T16:24:07.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714602/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714602/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714602/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-28","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 23 March 2017 to Question 68479, on Compass: contacts, if she will make an estimate of the number of service providers that cover the cost of landlord insurance.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","69554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714603","Home Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 8 March 2017, UIN 65925.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-04-18T16:35:53.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714603/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714603/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714603/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-28","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 8 March 2017 to Question 65925, on police: finance, if she will publish the real term change in aggregate central grant funding, excluding precept, for each police force in England and Wales from 2010-11 to 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","69553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714604","Home Office","false","2017-04-18","<p>The Government set out the process for estimating costs to the police and the Home Office for the grant, renewal and variation of section 5 licences in the impact assessment accompanying the consultation on firearms fees, which was published on 12 January. The impact assessment explains that the Home Office costs were calculated by assessing the full cost of the licensing firearms service, and then estimating the cost of each application type through a costing exercise that assessed the time taken for each application. Police costs were estimated based on the unit costs used to set new fees for police administered firearms licences in April 2015. The impact assessment is available on <a href="http://www.gov.uk" target="_blank">www.gov.uk</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-04-18T16:35:03.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714604/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714604/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714604/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-28","Firearms: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the process is for estimating costs to (a) the police and (b) her Department for the grant and renewal of authorities under section 5 of the Firearms Act 1968.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","69557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714605","Home Office","false","2017-03-31","<p>The National Transfer Protocol, which provides guidance on the operation of the National Transfer Scheme and can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/534258/Interim_National_UASC_transfer_protocol.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/534258/Interim_National_UASC_transfer_protocol.pdf</a>, sets out that a child’s best interests must be at the heart of transfer decisions. This will include taking account of an unaccompanied child’s peer and sibling groups and ensuring that unaccompanied children can maintain contact and, wherever possible, are placed in the same local authority area as their siblings.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-31T13:14:27.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714605/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714605/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714605/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-28","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government takes to minimise the separation of peer and sibling groups among unaccompanied asylum-seeking children as part of the National Transfer Scheme.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","69504"
