for standard electricity and 15,000kWh for gas. Data are taken from tables 2.2.1 and 2.3.1 of energy prices: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/annual-domestic-energy-price-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/annual-domestic-energy-price-statistics</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-04-18T12:33:26.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714714/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714714/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-28","Energy: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 23 March 2017 to Question 68609, what estimate his Department has made of the average (a) spend on household energy bills as a percentage of household expenditure and (b) real term spent per household on energy bills in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","69551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714715","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy published the ‘ECO: Help to Heat’ Final Stage Impact Assessment in January 2017. The number of homes treated under ECO 2 (April 2015 – March 2017) and the estimated number of homes treated under the ECO extension period (April 2017 – September 2018) are presented in section 9.4 (page 10) in the Final Stage Impact Assessment. <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/586266/ECO_Transition_Final_Stage_IA__For_Publication_.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/586266/ECO_Transition_Final_Stage_IA__For_Publication_.pdf</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-04-20T13:41:10.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714715/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714715/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-28","Housing: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 24 March 2017 to Question 68280, if he will publish the evidential basis for the statement that 500,000 homes will be insulated between April 2017 and September 2018; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","69552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714717","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-18","<p>A competitive and transparent financial services sector is vital to ensuring that the UK economy delivers for consumers and businesses.</p><p>The Government has not yet made an assessment of the effect of pricing structures used by foreign currency providers on competition for consumers or UK small businesses which trade overseas but, as with all policy areas, keeps transparency of foreign exchange fees under review.</p><p>The Government is currently conducting research on the effects of transparency on consumer decisions to inform its policy approach. The Government has recently consulted on draft regulations for the implementation of the Second Payment Service Directive, and will respond in due course.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","69488","2017-04-18T14:14:41.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714717/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714717/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-28","Bureaux de Change: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made on the effect of non-transparent or opaque pricing structures used by foreign currency providers on competition for consumers.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","69490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714718","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-03","<p>The Department considers funding for a range of research activities and is carefully considering the recommendations contained in Charles Hendry’s recent report on tidal lagoons.</p><p>Any decisions arising from the Review, including whether to proceed with the Swansea Bay project, will need to balance the priorities of security of supply, affordability and meeting our climate change obligations.</p><p>We understand that Natural Resources Wales are currently examining the developer’s marine licence application.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-04-03T13:21:24.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714718/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714718/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-28","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will provide research funding for an assessment of the potential effect of the Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon on 10 year fishing spawning cycles; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","69508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714719","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-03","<p>We understand that Natural Resource Wales are currently examining the developer’s marine licence application.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-04-03T13:22:50.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714719/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714719/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-28","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether a marine licence has been granted for the proposed development of the  Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","69509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714720","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-31","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Blackley and Broughton (Graham Stringer) on 16 March 2017 to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-03-08/67031/" target="_blank">67031</a>.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-31T12:43:04.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714720/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714720/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-28","Electric Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to prepare the national grid for a potential increase in the use of electric cars.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","69528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714721","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-03","<p>Local Enterprise Partnerships are bringing together the public and private sector with universities, colleges and other local organisations, to ensure investment is made where it will generate the most jobs and growth.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has invested £379.6m in the North East Local Enterprise Partnership area through three rounds of Growth Deals. The Easington constituency has benefitted directly through the Horden (Peterlee) Station project and the improvement to the A19/A189 Seaham/Murton interchange. Both projects will help the residents of Easington and the North East to access new and existing job opportunities.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-04-03T13:39:55.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714721/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714721/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-28","Local Enterprise Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of local enterprise partnerships in delivering employment, growth and investment (a) nationally, (b) in the North East and (c) in Easington constituency.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","69543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714722","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-18","<p>A competitive and transparent financial services sector is vital to ensuring that the UK economy delivers for consumers and businesses.</p><p>The Government has not yet made an assessment of the effect of pricing structures used by foreign currency providers on competition for consumers or UK small businesses which trade overseas but, as with all policy areas, keeps transparency of foreign exchange fees under review.</p><p>The Government is currently conducting research on the effects of transparency on consumer decisions to inform its policy approach. The Government has recently consulted on draft regulations for the implementation of the Second Payment Service Directive, and will respond in due course.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","69490","2017-04-18T14:14:42.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714722/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714722/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-28","Foreign Exchange: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of non-transparent pricing structures in foreign currency exchange on UK small businesses which trade overseas.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","69488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714723","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-03","<p>As announced at Budget 2016, the Government will rebalance the Climate Change Levy (CCL) rates between energy sources from 2019-20.</p><p> </p><p>In 2019-20, the electricity to gas rates will move from a ratio of 2.9:1 to 2.5:1. Liquefied Petroleum Gas and other taxable fuel rates will be increased in proportion to the rate for gas. The Government intends to further rebalance the electricity to gas ratio to 1:1 by 2025.</p><p> </p><p>This continues to ensure that the CCL encourages the efficient use of energy by businesses and reduces emissions by creating incentives to source electricity from renewable sources.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-04-03T10:57:43.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714723/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714723/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-28","Climate Change Levy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of recent changes to the climate change levy on the policy to move off-gas grid businesses away from oil, coal and other higher carbon fuels.","false","Biography information for Chris Davies","Brecon and Radnorshire","Chris Davies","69531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714724","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-18","<p>In respect of (a) the responsibility for deciding whether to grant a lease rests with the Crown Estate and not the Department. We understand that discussions are ongoing but as yet a lease has not been granted. In respect of (b) the Contract for Difference negotiations are commercially sensitive and it is not appropriate for us to comment on the proposals that have been received.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-04-18T12:55:16.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714724/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714724/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-28","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether (a) a lease has been granted from the Crown Estates for the development of the Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon and (b) contracts for four different strike prices have been received; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","69571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714725","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-03","<p>In 2010, the Department of Energy and Climate Change (DECC) published its feasibility assessment of a scheme to generate electricity from the tides of the Severn estuary. It found that, since the Severn estuary is highly dynamic, and without detailed information on specific projects, it was impossible to predict the impacts of the tidal power schemes surveyed with absolute certainty.</p><p>Environmental impacts, along with other relevant matters, would be considered as part of the relevant statutory planning processes when consent applications for tidal energy generation projects are submitted.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-04-03T13:20:31.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714725/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714725/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-28","Tidal Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of alternative forms of tidal energy generation; what the result of the modelling of those alternatives was; what assessment was made of the effect of each such alternative on (a) coastal erosion and (b) sediment build-up; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","69595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714726","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-18","<p>As set out in the Industrial Strategy Green Paper, the Government is carefully considering the future of European Structural and Investment Funds following the UK’s exit from the European Union. We welcome views on this, including through responses to the Green Paper consultation, which was open until 17 April.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-04-18T10:21:13.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714726/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714726/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-28","Regeneration: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government plans to develop schemes to replace existing EU regeneration funding after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","69462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714727","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-18","<p>To deliver an effective Industrial Strategy that works for everyone, it is important to build on local strengths to boost growth nationwide. We want the whole country to be engaged, from businesses, workers, consumers, the research community, and from local leaders – including councils.</p><p>The Industrial Strategy Green Paper marked the beginning of our consultation. Since its publication we have been engaging extensively with key stakeholders, including local councils and Local Enterprise Partnerships. We will of course continue to work with local councils, as they have an important role to play in a successful Industrial Strategy.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-04-18T10:26:36.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714727/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714727/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-28","Economic Growth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans the Government has to give local councils a role in developing the Government's industrial strategy and to enable them to support local economic growth.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","69463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714728","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-18","<p>The Department for International Trade is working closely with the Department for International Development to ensure that development and global prosperity are at the heart of UK trade and investment policy. We recognise the need for a smooth transition which minimises disruption to our trading relationships.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-04-18T15:44:08.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714728/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714728/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-28","UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what plans his Department has to ensure that the UK's trade arrangements with the EU after the UK has left the EU do not adversely affect the world's poorest people.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","69465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714730","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-04","<p>Guidance on the GOV.UK website covers export controls and export licensing, including which exports are controlled, how to apply for a licence and exporter responsibilities. In addition we run introductory and intermediate training events, up and down the country, on different aspects of exports controls. Exporters may also sign up for regular bulletins on changes in policy and licensing.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-04-04T12:41:23.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714730/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714730/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-28","Exports: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what guidance is available to businesses on obtaining an export license.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","69459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714731","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-04","<p>The Department for International Trade supports first-time exporters through a variety of tailored services.</p><p>Our digital platform GREAT.GOV.UK provides businesses access to millions of pounds’ worth of potential overseas business to help them start or continue exporting; and provides a new searchable export directory to match businesses according to the worldwide demand for UK goods and services.</p><p>UK Export Finance (UKEF), the UK’s export credit agency, helps UK companies of all sizes and in all sectors win, fulfil and get paid for exports. Its regional Export Finance Managers are the first point of contact for guidance for UK exporters, including first time export businesses.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-04-04T12:40:19.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714731/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714731/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-28","Exports: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what support he plans to provide to assist first-time export businesses; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","69460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714732","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-05","<p>The independent Matthew Taylor review on employment practices in a modern economy is considering the impact of non-standard working arrangements on employment status and employment rights, and as part of his review he has considered a range of available papers, including Julie Deane’s Review. That review will be reporting in the summer.</p><p>We have also announced we will be looking at parental benefits for the self-employed.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","69370","2017-04-05T13:01:32.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714732/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714732/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-28","Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the recommendation of the publication of the Julie Dean Self-Employment Review, what steps he has taken to review the equal treatment and recognition for the self-employed in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","69369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714733","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-05","<p>The independent Matthew Taylor review on employment practices in a modern economy is considering the impact of non-standard working arrangements on employment status and employment rights, and as part of his review he has considered a range of available papers, including Julie Deane’s Review. That review will be reporting in the summer.</p><p>We have also announced we will be looking at parental benefits for the self-employed.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","69369","2017-04-05T13:01:32.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714733/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714733/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-28","Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the recommendation of the publication of the Julie Dean Self-Employment Review, what steps he has taken to calculate the effect new policies will have on the self-employed sector in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","69370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714734","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-03","<p>A self-employed individual decides how they undertake work. This could include identifying a suitable role via an agency and it is for the work-seeker and agency to agree the type of contract that they will be engaged under.</p><p> </p><p>Individuals seeking work through an agency, regardless of circumstances outside of the agency relationship, are protected by the Conduct of Employment Agencies and Employment Businesses Regulation 2003 and the Agency Worker Regulations 2010.</p><p> </p><p>The Taylor review on modern employment practices is considering the impact of non-standard working arrangements on employment status and employment rights.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-04-03T13:26:49.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714734/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714734/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-28","Self-employed: Agency Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he has taken to tackle the use of self-employed people as agency workers by businesses.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","69371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714735","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-18","<p>We have received a wide range of thoughtful and constructive responses to the consultation on the Government’s Corporate Governance Reform Green Paper. We are very grateful to all those who have contributed to the debate, and will respond once we have fully considered their views.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-04-18T10:22:49.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714735/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714735/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-28","Company Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will provide a date of publication for the Corporate Governance White Paper.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","69393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714736","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-04","<p>The Prime Minister’s first bilateral visit beyond Europe was to India. Joined by my Rt Hon. Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade and myself, she led a UK business delegation, to meet with key Indian businesses and senior officials.</p><p> </p><p>She met Prime Minister Modi, opened the India-UK Tech Summit, and announced £1.2bn of commercial deals. Both governments committed to building the “closest possible trade and economic relationship”.</p><p> </p><p>My Rt Hon. Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade co-chairs the India/UK Joint Economic and Trade Committee, and established a Joint Working Group to review and strengthen our trading relationship, both now and when we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>UK Export Finance has considerable appetite to support UK exports to India and welcomes new applications for support.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-04-04T12:39:04.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714736/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714736/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-28","Overseas Trade: India","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps his Department is taking to improve bilateral trade with India.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","69481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714737","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-03","<p>The full list of tariffs is contained in the Integrated Tariff of the United Kingdom, which publishes the schedule of duty rates for over 16,600 commodities. This information is available online here:</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/trade-tariff/sections" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/trade-tariff/sections</a></p><p>Specific information relating to the revenue yield for each commodity code is not collated in a readily available format by HM Revenue and Customs.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-04-03T10:47:22.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714737/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714737/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-28","Import Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will place in the Library a full list of tariffed commodities with their identifying codes and their annual revenues for 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","69548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714738","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-18","<p>As the Prime Minister has highlighted, during negotiations she will represent every person in the whole United Kingdom and we are working with the administrations in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland to deliver an outcome that works for the whole of the UK. The Government has also set this out in the ‘Plan for Britain’, which identifies the desire to ensure that big decisions benefit the whole country, creating jobs and supporting cities towns and communities right across the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-04-18T13:26:21.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714738/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714738/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-28","Economic Growth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will take steps to ensure that job creation and economic development across the whole of the UK is a priority during negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","69650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714739","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-18","<p>Information relating to the Department’s expenditure in 2016-17 will be published in the Annual Report in Summer 2017.<br><br>Data relating to spend over £25,000 and contracts over £10,000 will be published as part of regular transparency releases on GOV.uk.<strong> <br></strong></p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-04-18T13:22:33.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714739/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714739/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-28","Department for Exiting the European Union: Management Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 27 February 2017 to Question 65684, what the procurement spend of his Department has been since its creation; and what proportion of that spend has been on management consultants.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","69467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714740","Home Office","false","2017-04-04","<p>On 29 March, the Prime Minister formally notified the EU of the Government’s decision to invoke Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union and withdraw from the EU. In future the Free Movement Directive will no longer apply and the migration of EU nationals will be subject to UK law. The notification letter makes clear that the Government wants to strike an early agreement about the rights of EU citizens who are already living in the UK, and UK citizens living in the EU, giving citizens as much certainty as possible.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-04-04T15:43:15.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714740/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714740/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-28","Immigration: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 21 March 2017 to Question 68205, what the Government's policy is on retrospective removal of the status of non-UK EEA nationals who have already automatically achieved permanent residence status by exercising their treaty rights as an EEA national in the UK for five years.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","69420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714741","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-18","<p>In its response to the Independent Review of the Money Advice Service (March 2015), the coalition government agreed to review the legal framework for debt administration, and to consider the impacts of additional statutory protections for consumers.</p><p> </p><p>As I said in Parliament on 29 March, the government is looking carefully at a breathing space scheme for England and Wales, and fully supports the principles of better debt management and lower levels of problem debt. However, any new spending proposals must be considered carefully. The government will continue to look into the options for a breathing space scheme.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-04-18T14:22:54.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714741/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714741/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-28","Debts: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the Debt Arrangement Scheme in Scotland; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","69466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714745","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-07","<p>As indicated in the answer of 31 January, the Government’s view is that although Transport for London (TfL) do not have the power to limit the number of private hire vehicles (PHVs), other mechanisms are available to address concerns regarding the operation of the taxi and private hire sector. Therefore there are no current plans to amend primary legislation in order to permit any licensing authority, including TfL, to cap the number of PHVs licensed.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-04-07T12:31:02.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714745/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714745/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-28","Taxis: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 31 January (HL4755), whether the range of tools available to Transport for London to deal with congestion and vehicle pollution includes the power to limit the number of private hire vehicles which it licenses; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Higgins",,"Lord Higgins","HL6365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714746","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-07","<p>The Government supports choice for consumers, and wants to see both taxis and private hire vehicles prosper in London and across the country. As indicated in the answer of 31 January, the Government’s view is that although powers to limit the number of private hire vehicles do not exist, other mechanisms are available to address concerns regarding the operation of the taxi and private hire sector.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has met with representatives of the Mayor on this issue.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-04-07T12:30:29.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714746/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714746/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-28","Taxis: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 31 January (HL4755), whether any authority has the power to limit the number of private hire vehicles licensed to operate in London; and whether they have received any representations from the Mayor of London on the need for such powers.","false","Biography information for Lord Higgins",,"Lord Higgins","HL6366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714747","Home Office","false","2017-04-11","<p>The National Crime Agency, of which the CEOP Command forms part, publishes the National Strategic Assessment annually. The Assessment provides a comprehensive picture of the risk posed to the UK and its interests by serious and organised crime, including child sexual exploitation and abuse.</p><p>The National Crime Agency also publishes an Annual Report which contains a set of statistics in respect of the whole of its activity.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL6368","2017-04-11T13:27:39.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714747/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714747/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-28","Offences against Children: Internet","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment the Child Exploitation and Online Protection Centre has made of the extent of child sexual abuse and exploitation online; which groups of children are particularly at risk; and whether there is evidence of a growing problem of online sexual risk for UK children.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL6367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714748","Home Office","false","2017-04-11","<p>The National Crime Agency, of which the CEOP Command forms part, publishes the National Strategic Assessment annually. The Assessment provides a comprehensive picture of the risk posed to the UK and its interests by serious and organised crime, including child sexual exploitation and abuse.</p><p>The National Crime Agency also publishes an Annual Report which contains a set of statistics in respect of the whole of its activity.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL6367","2017-04-11T13:27:39.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714748/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714748/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-28","Child Exploitation and Online Protection Centre","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Child Exploitation and Online Protection Centre has published any statistics in publicly available research reports since 2013; and if not, whether it has any plans to do so in the short term.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL6368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714749","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-07","<p>The Government plans to negotiate the best possible relationship between the UK and the EU in the field of aviation with a smooth and orderly transition. The Department for Transport is working closely with the industry to best understand their requirements and to ensure that the outcome of the negotiations serves the interests of both passengers and the aviation industry.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-04-07T12:29:55.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714749/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714749/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-28","Air Routes: Europe","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to ensure that, following Brexit, airlines based in the UK will still be able to operate European flights; and what assurances they are able to give to the public, airports and airlines, that tickets sold up to eighteen months ahead can be honoured post-Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Teverson",,"Lord Teverson","HL6369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714750","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-07","<p>The Government plans to negotiate the best possible relationship between the UK and the EU in the field of aviation with a smooth and orderly transition. The Department for Transport is working closely with the industry to best understand their requirements and to ensure that the outcome of the negotiations serves the interests of both passengers and the aviation industry.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-04-07T12:29:33.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714750/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714750/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-28","Air Routes: Europe","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to negotiate, during the Brexit negotiations, a transitional aviation regime for UK airlines operating European routes, in order to avoid a sudden end to the operation of those routes; and if so, (1) how they intend to conduct, and (2) when they expect to conclude, those negotiations.","false","Biography information for Lord Teverson",,"Lord Teverson","HL6370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714751","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>Data on the cost of mesothelioma to the National Health Service is not collected centrally.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-04-05T14:18:08.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714751/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714751/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","Mesothelioma","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord O’Shaughnessy on 27 March, whether any data is collected on the cost of mesothelioma to the NHS; and if so, what.","false","Biography information for Lord Wills",,"Lord Wills","HL6371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714752","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) has advised the expert panel considered all the evidence that it believed was relevant to the safety and efficacy of mitochondrial donation techniques. The panel did not make any recommendations relating to epigenetics and so the HFEA has placed no such requirements on centres wishing to offer mitochondrial donation.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-04-05T14:17:54.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714752/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714752/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","In Vitro Fertilisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, following the award by the Licence Committee of the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority of a licence to Centre 0017 to carry out pronuclear transfer between embryos to prevent transmission of serious mitochondrial disease, what safeguards Centre 0017 has put in place to ensure that early pronuclear transfer will take place during treatment at precisely the same epigenetic stage in donor and recipient embryos, given the rapid rate of DNA demethylation and the different rates of embryo development at the early pronuclear stage.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714753","Department of Health","false","2017-04-05","<p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority has advised that it is a condition of a licence that CE marked medical devices must be used wherever possible. In the case of pronuclear transfer, there are no appropriate CE marked reagents, meaning that for treatment to take place, non-CE marked reagents must be used. In this case, the centre must adhere to paragraph 26.5 in Guidance Note 26 of the Authority’s code of practice, which states that if a centre modifies a CE marked product or uses a product “off label”, it must complete a risk assessment and validation to ensure the product is safe. A copy of the Guidance Note 26 is attached.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-04-05T14:18:48.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714753/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714753/answer","Guidance_Note_26_-_Equipment_and_materials.pdf","Guidance_Note_26_-_Equipment_and_materials.pdf","Guidance Note 26","Guidance Note 26","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714753/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","In Vitro Fertilisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, with reference to paragraph 2.3 of the minutes of 9 March 2017 of the Licence Committee of the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority, which non-CE marked reagents will be used by Centre 0017 for the purposes of treatment involving pronuclear transfer between embryos to prevent transmission of serious mitochondrial disease; which laboratories will test the non-CE marked reagents for sterility and toxicity; and why non-CE marked reagents are being used.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714754","Department of Health","false","2017-04-06","<p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) has advised that, as set out in Guidance Note 33 of the Authority’s code of practice, centres carrying out mitochondrial donation are required to have documented processes in place setting out how the health of children born from mitochondrial donation will be followed up. A copy of Guidance Note 33 is attached.</p><p> </p><p>If the centre becomes aware that any child born as a result of mitochondrial donation has a mitochondrial disease, birth defect, genetic abnormality or if there has been any other adverse outcome, the centre must report this to the HFEA in accordance with the adverse incidents requirements set out in Guidance Note 27 of the code of practice. A copy of Guidance Note 27 is attached.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-04-06T10:53:18.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714754/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714754/answer","CoP_June_2016_GN33.pdf ; CoP_June_2016_GN27.pdf","CoP_June_2016_GN33.pdf ; CoP_June_2016_GN27.pdf","Guidance Note 33 ; Guidance Note 27","Guidance Note 33 ; Guidance Note 27","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714754/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-28","In Vitro Fertilisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, with reference to paragraph 2.8 of the minutes of 9 March 2017 of the Licence Committee of the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) regarding babies born following pronuclear transfer between embryos, what procedures are in place to (1) identify whether a child born following pronuclear transfer is born with (a) a mitochondrial disease, (b) a genetic or epigenetic abnormality, (c) a birth defect, or (d) some other adverse outcome, (2) notify the HFEA in cases of any such adverse outcome, and (3) identify any such adverse outcome and notify the HFEA where consent for follow-up has not been granted.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714755","Department for International Development","false","2017-04-04","<p>While there is no specific reference in the DFID Policy Paper, the UK’s commitment to Leave No One Behind encompasses a broad range of discriminated and marginalised groups - age, sex, disability, race, ethnicity, origin, religion or economic or other status, such as language, LGBT, migratory status or geographic location. Leave No One Behind means tackling the root causes of extreme poverty and exclusion for different groups – including on the basis of religion – by ensuring opportunities for all, both now and in the future. It commits the UK to set a of actions to ensure that; people who are furthest behind, who have least opportunity and who are the most excluded will be prioritised.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-04-04T15:43:18.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714755/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714755/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-28","Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why no reference to (1) targeted and persecuted religious minorities, or (2) the fundamental human right of freedom of religion and belief, is made in the goals specified in the Department for International Development policy paper, <i>Agenda 2030: Delivering the Global Goals</i>.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714756","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-05","<p>Advancing human rights - including the right to freedom of religion and belief (FoRB) - is embedded across the work of our diplomats. In order to enhance the capabilities of staff working to promote FoRB in their country context, the FCO issued a revised toolkit in October 2016. This coincided with our London Conference on FoRB and Countering Violent Extremism, which was attended by a number of country desk officers. The FCO also routinely provides training and seminars to increase religious literacy amongst staff.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-05T15:50:27.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714756/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714756/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what instructions have been given to FCO country desk officers to ensure that freedom of religion or belief is included in their work.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714757","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-07","<p>The International Civil Aviation Organisation Technical Instructions for the Safe Transport of Dangerous Goods by Air (and the International Air Transport Association Dangerous Goods Regulations) detail the conditions for the carriage of consumer Portable Electronic Devices (PEDs) containing lithium ion/metal batteries by passengers and crew. Carriage within checked/hold baggage is permitted with the devices switched off and packed such that they are afforded suitable protection from damage and inadvertent operation.</p><p> </p><p>The Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) has provided further advice to air carriers on the procedures to be followed in relation to the carriage of devices containing lithium batteries in the hold of an aircraft. With assurance that these procedures are in place and that passengers are complying with the operators’ safety instructions, the CAA’s assessment is that the safety risk in relation to this issue can be managed.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-04-07T12:29:10.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714757/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714757/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-28","Aviation: Security","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, before introducing the ban on the carriage of personal electronic devices in cabins on certain flights, what assessment they made of (1) the additional risk of lithium battery fires in aircraft holds, and (2) the safety implications of implementing a ban on lithium batteries being transported in any part of the aircraft.","true","Biography information for Lord Balfe",,"Lord Balfe","HL6377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714758","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-11","<p>​Ministers and officials have repeatedly made representations to the Iranian Government on all consular cases involving British nationals in Iran, including Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe's. On 17 February, the Foreign Secretary discussed Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe's case, including her health, with the Iranian Foreign Minister. Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe's family confirmed that a specialist visited her on 19 February. The Iranian authorities have given us their assurances that Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe will receive medical treatment if appropriate. We have repeatedly requested consular access so that we can be assured of her welfare, however the Iranian position on dual nationality makes progress difficult. We urge the Iranian authorities to ensure action is taken on the specialist's assessment and will pursue this at every opportunity.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-11T14:48:32.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714758/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714758/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Iran about the provision of appropriate medical treatment for Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe and about ensuring her general welfare.","false","Biography information for Lord Bird",,"Lord Bird","HL6378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714759","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-11","<p>I refer the noble Lord to my previous answer to him on 27 March - PQ HL6120.</p><p>As stated in the Housing White Paper, the Government will in due course set out a rent policy for social landlords for the period beyond 2020 to help them to borrow against future income. Our aim is to ensure that they have the confidence they need about their future income in order to plan ahead.</p><p /><p />",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-04-11T15:45:21.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714759/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714759/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-28","Council Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact of the reduction in council housing rents on (1) the maintenance and improvement of the existing council housing stock, and (2) the building of new council houses between now and 2022.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL6379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714760","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-07","<p>The rise in the level of self-inflicted deaths is complex and there is no simple solution. We are committed to driving improvement across the system to bring the rate down by increasing the support available to vulnerable offenders during the first 24 hours in custody. We have invested more in mental health training for prison officers and are delivering a suicide and self-harm reduction project to address the rise in self-inflicted deaths and self-harm in female prisons. This year, we will publish a strategy for female offenders that will focus on how we improve outcomes for female offenders in the community as well as in custody.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-04-07T12:20:22.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714760/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714760/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-28","Prisoners: Suicide","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the conclusion of the Prison and Probation Ombudsman in the bulletin published on 28 March that there has been a "lack of concerted and sustained action" to deal with the rise in the number of suicides by female prisoners, what steps they have taken to implement recommendations made in the Corston Report published in 2007, and since, to address that.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL6380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714761","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-04","<p>I would refer the Noble Lord to the Written Statement by the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions made in the other place on 15 September 2016 (attached) about supported accommodation, which made clear we will consider what level of new burdens funding would be appropriate to enable local authorities to fulfil their new role.</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2016-09-15/HCWS154/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2016-09-15/HCWS154/</a></p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-04-04T15:26:31.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714761/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714761/answer","170404 HL6381.pdf","170404 HL6381.pdf","Written Statement HCWS154","Written Statement HCWS154","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714761/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-28","Supported Housing: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, in the light of their intention to devolve discretionary funding on supported housing costs to English local authorities, funding will be provided for such councils under the new burdens doctrine.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL6381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714762","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-11","<p>Since the UK Statistics Authority report on homelessness statistics was published DCLG have engaged in detailed discussions with UK Statistics Authority officials. We have met the requirements set out below, and will continue to work with the UK Statistics Authority to make our homelessness statistics as robust and accessible as possible.</p><p>We have implemented the key requirement to combine the publication of statistics on statutory homelessness and prevention and relief. We have also enhanced our user engagement structures, and based on user discussions have embarked on a project to redesign the form which collects homelessness data. We have also added harmonised region codes to local authority datasets to allow users to easily re-use the data for regional analysis and have published demographic and time series data on rough sleepers for the first time.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-04-11T15:44:52.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714762/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714762/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-28","Homelessness: Statistics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress has been made in implementing the recommendations made by the UK Statistics Authority following the 2015 review of the statistics in relation to homelessness and rough sleeping.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL6382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714763","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-07","<p>We are investing £1.3bn to build up to 10,000 new prison places which will replace places in ageing and ineffective prisons, such as HMP Dartmoor, providing buildings fit for today’s demands and able to support effective rehabilitation.</p><p> </p><p>HMP Berwyn, a new rehabilitative male prison in North Wales, opened week beginning 27 February 2017, providing 2,106 modern and efficient prison places.</p><p> </p><p>We have applied for planning permission to redevelop the sites at the former HMP Wellingborough and at HMP &amp; YOI Glen Parva.</p><p> </p><p>We intend to apply for planning permission on the sites of HMP &amp; YOI Rochester and HMP &amp; YOI Hindley, on land adjacent to HMP Full Sutton and a new site in Port Talbot.</p><p> </p><p>Notice to terminate the lease for Dartmoor prison was served to the Duchy of Cornwall in November 2013.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL6384","2017-04-07T12:28:10.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714763/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714763/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-28","Dartmoor Prison","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they have taken to replace Dartmoor Prison since the publication of the report of the House of Commons Justice Committee, <i>Prisons: planning and policies</i>, of March 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL6383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714764","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-07","<p>We are investing £1.3bn to build up to 10,000 new prison places which will replace places in ageing and ineffective prisons, such as HMP Dartmoor, providing buildings fit for today’s demands and able to support effective rehabilitation.</p><p> </p><p>HMP Berwyn, a new rehabilitative male prison in North Wales, opened week beginning 27 February 2017, providing 2,106 modern and efficient prison places.</p><p> </p><p>We have applied for planning permission to redevelop the sites at the former HMP Wellingborough and at HMP &amp; YOI Glen Parva.</p><p> </p><p>We intend to apply for planning permission on the sites of HMP &amp; YOI Rochester and HMP &amp; YOI Hindley, on land adjacent to HMP Full Sutton and a new site in Port Talbot.</p><p> </p><p>Notice to terminate the lease for Dartmoor prison was served to the Duchy of Cornwall in November 2013.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL6383","2017-04-07T12:28:10.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714764/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714764/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-28","Dartmoor Prison","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the need to give ten years' notice to the Duchy of Cornwall to vacate Dartmoor Prison, whether and when they intend (1) to give such notice, and (2) to replace it with a new prison.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL6384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714765","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-07","<p>The trial is now in its fifth year and the evidence so far suggests that these vehicles are proving to be a more efficient way of moving the same volume of freight, using fewer vehicles, mainly on trunking routes. The trial has demonstrated that longer semi-trailers (LSTs) have reduced the number of journeys and vehicles on the road, saving an estimated 75-90,000 lorry journeys and 10 million km, to the end of 2015. This represents an average of 1 in 19 journeys saved compared to using regular semi-trailers. All the evidence to date indicates LSTs on the trial are operating as safely as standard length semi-trailers. The latest year of trial data is currently being processed and that the Department for Transport anticipates publishing a 2016 annual report in due course.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-04-07T12:27:23.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714765/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714765/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-28","Large Goods Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what lessons have been learned from the trials that have taken place on the use of longer semi-trailers for articulated goods vehicles.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL6385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714766","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-07","<p>We asked the trial evaluators to assess all incidents including reported damage only events. The damage-only incidents logged on the trial are summarised in the annual report. The majority of the events involved only minor damage. We have no record of incidents involving longer semi-trailers (LSTs) regularly causing significant damage to street furniture or buildings.</p><p> </p><p>LSTs operate within existing weight restrictions and have reduced the number of journeys and therefore are unlikely to have had any effect on highway surfaces through extra overall or axle weight. LSTs are required to meet current Construction and Use turning circle requirements by physical tests being conducted and witnessed by Vehicle Certification Agency engineers. During these witness test the trailers demonstrate less tyre side scrub and less apparent damage to the test surface.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-04-07T12:25:42.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714766/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714766/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-28","Large Goods Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the effect on highway surfaces and street furniture, such as roundabouts, of the use of longer semi-trailers for articulated goods vehicles.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL6386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714767","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-07","<p>The trial is now in its fifth year and the evidence so far suggests that these vehicles are proving to be a more efficient way of moving the same volume of freight, using fewer vehicles, mainly on our trunking routes. A decision will be made on the future of longer semi-trailers (LSTs) when we have sufficient evidence from the trial. Officials anticipate stating discussions with interested external organisations in the next few months about the potential future use of LSTs.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-04-07T12:24:47.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714767/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714767/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-28","Large Goods Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what are their plans for the future use of longer semi-trailers for articulated goods vehicles.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL6387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714768","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-07","<p>A decision has not been taken whether (and if so how) to allow longer semi-trailers (LSTs) outside the trial. In the trial LSTs have access to the general highway network. We will use the evidence from the ongoing trial to inform any decisions about future use. The evidence from the trial to date demonstrates that the majority of LST operations take place on motorways. However these vehicles need ready access to depots, supplier sites and larger retail sites, in many cases near but not on motorways or trunk roads. Local Authorities have powers to restrict or prohibit the use of heavy goods vehicles on specific roads. These restrictions could also apply to LSTs.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-04-07T12:33:17.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714768/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714768/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-28","Large Goods Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend longer semi-trailers for articulated goods vehicles to have unfettered use of the entire highway network or be confined to trunk roads and motorways.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL6388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714769","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-11","<p>We will continue to raise our concerns over the treatment of Palestinian minors, particularly those in Israeli military detention, with the Israeli authorities on a regular basis.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-11T14:49:38.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714769/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714769/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714769/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-28","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 23 March (HL6002), and in the light of reports by Amnesty International and Defence for Children International–Palestine drawing attention to the treatment of Palestinian children following their arrest by Israeli forces, what action they intend to take to protect those children.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL6389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714770","Cabinet Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>All central government departments are responsible for their own procurement.</p><p> </p><p>The Crown Commercial Service (CCS) provides a range of commercial services to the public sector to enable departments to achieve best value for money from their procurement.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-04-03T16:14:28.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714770/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714770/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-28","Government Departments: Procurement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which government departments are responsible for their own procurement.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL6390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714771","Cabinet Office","false","2017-04-03","<p>HM Government works with a number of professional bodies to discharge its procurement and commercial activities, principally the Chartered Institute of Procurement and Supply (CIPS) and the International Association for Contract and Commercial Management (IACCM).</p><p> </p><p>A detailed breakdown of departments’ dealings with these organisations is not held centrally.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-04-03T16:14:06.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714771/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714771/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714771/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-28","Government Departments: Procurement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government from which professional bodies the civil service seeks support to discharge procurement responsibilities, broken down by department.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL6391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714772","Home Office","false","2017-04-06","<p>The Home Office’s Building a Stronger Britain Together (BSBT) Programme was established in early 2016 to deliver Pillars 1 and 2 of the Government’s Counter Extremism Strategy (countering extremist ideology, and building a partnership with those opposed to extremism). The Programme is designed to fulfil the Government’s commitment to ‘develop a new network, linking individuals and groups around Britain who are already standing up to extremists in their communities’. Its objectives include reducing the number of people holding attitudes, beliefs and feelings that oppose shared values; an increased sense of belonging and civic participation at a local level; and more resilient communities.</p><p> </p><p>Fifty-three groups have been awarded support from the first round of applications under BSBT. The Home Office will announce the groups and publish details of the projects it is supporting shortly.</p><p> </p><p>DfE and the Home Office are jointly funding Breakthrough Media to manage the Educate Against Hate website, which aims to provide teachers, school leaders and parents with the information, guidance and support they need to challenge radical views and keep their children safe, including supporting the promotion of fundamental British values.</p><p> </p><p>In 27 January 2017, the Department for Education awarded a contract to the Association of Citizenship teaching to produce 6 resource packs to include high quality guidance for teachers to hold knowledge-based debates on topical issues relating to fundamental British values (democracy, the rule of law, individual liberty, mutual respect for and tolerance of those with different beliefs and those without faith), citizenship and equality.</p><p> </p><p>The general reporting areas for school inspection are set out in section 5 of the Education Act 2005. Within this context, HM Chief Inspector is responsible for Ofsted’s common inspection framework and school inspection handbook, which set out how inspectors consider and report on these matters. In developing the framework and handbook, the Chief Inspector takes account of Departmental guidance to schools. This includes guidance on schools’ promotion of fundamental British values.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-04-06T15:13:54.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714772/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714772/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-28","Citizenship: Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what national or local (1) organisations, and (2) agencies, have been funded in the last 12 months in respect of the promotion of British values and associated work; and what guidance has been given to the Office for Standards in Education in relation to (a) inspection reporting on citizenship, British values and character building, as part of the national curriculum, and (b) the judgements made on the quality of education in both primary and secondary schools.","false","Biography information for Lord Blunkett",,"Lord Blunkett","HL6392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714773","Department for Education","false","2017-04-07","<p>We trust schools to decide the funding and resources that they allocate to individual subjects within the curriculum, including citizenship.</p><p> </p><p>The Association of Citizenship Teaching won a tender with the Department to produce high quality resources, including guidance regarding the teaching of fundamental British values. This will enable teachers to engage pupils in the importance of democracy, the rule of law, individual liberty, mutual respect for and tolerance of those with different beliefs and those without faith, citizenship, and equality. The value of the contract is £50,000 and the first two resources are currently being piloted. The contract will conclude on 31 October 2018.</p><p> </p><p>DfE and the Home Office are jointly funding the Educate Against Hate website (www.educateagainsthate.com), a comprehensive online resource for teachers, education professionals and parents, offering advice on how to keep young people safe from harmful influences that could lead to radicalisation as well as practical tools to engage with students on these matters and to enable them to discuss and debate issues. The total amount spent in 2016/17 was £36,404.00; funding for 17/18 is not has not yet been agreed.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-04-07T12:26:50.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714773/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714773/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-28","Citizenship: Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much funding has been provided in respect of citizenship education and related issues, including British values, over the last 12 months; to which bodies that funding was provided; how much has been specifically allocated to individual projects; what is the timetable for the spending of that funding; and how much funding is available for 2017–18.","false","Biography information for Lord Blunkett",,"Lord Blunkett","HL6393"
